var tafsirData_16 = {
  1: {
    "The command of Allah is at hand,": "The decree of Allah, referring to the Day of Judgment, the punishment of the disbelievers, or the victory of the believers, is so certain that it is spoken of as if it has already arrived. In the sight of Allah, time is nothing—what He has promised will definitely happen. The disbelievers of Makkah used to mockingly ask the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) to hasten the punishment they were warned about. This verse affirms that it is coming without doubt, so there is no need for impatience or mockery.",
    "so do not hasten it.": "This is a response to those who challenged the Prophet by saying, \"If this punishment is real, why doesn't it come now?\" Allah is telling them not to rush, because everything happens according to His perfect timing and wisdom. Just as a farmer plants seeds and must wait for the harvest, Allah's decrees unfold at the appointed time. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"The Hour will not be established until...\" listing many signs, showing that Allah has a set plan that unfolds gradually.",
    "Glorified and Exalted is He above what they associate ˹with Him in worship˺!": "Allah declares His absolute purity and perfection, far removed from any partners, equals, or rivals. The polytheists attributed partners to Allah—idols, angels, or other beings—but Allah is infinitely greater than all of that. He alone is the Creator, Sustainer, and Controller of all things. Nothing resembles Him, and nothing deserves worship except Him. This phrase is a powerful rejection of all forms of shirk (associating partners with Allah)."
  },
  2: {
    "He sends down the angels with revelation by His command": "Allah sends the angels, particularly Jibreel (Gabriel), carrying the revelation—the Qur'an and divine guidance—which is called \"the spirit\" because it gives life to hearts just as the soul gives life to bodies. Without guidance, hearts are spiritually dead. This revelation comes by Allah's command, not randomly or by anyone's request. It is a planned mercy from Allah to guide humanity out of darkness into light.",
    "to whoever He wills of His servants,": "Allah chooses whom He blesses with prophethood and revelation. This is not something anyone can earn through wealth, status, or lineage—it is purely Allah's choice based on His infinite wisdom. He chose Muhammad (peace be upon him) just as He chose Musa, Isa, Ibrahim, and all the prophets before. The people of Quraysh questioned why Muhammad was chosen, but Allah knows best who is worthy of carrying His message.",
    "˹stating:˺ \"Warn ˹humanity˺ that there is no god ˹worthy of worship˺ except Me,": "The core message of every single prophet was the same: Tawheed—the absolute oneness of Allah in worship. From Adam to Muhammad (peace be upon them all), every messenger came with this same call. There is no deity worthy of worship except Allah. All the rituals, prayers, and devotion that people direct to idols, saints, or any created being are misplaced. True worship belongs only to the One who created everything.",
    "so be mindful of Me ˹alone˺.\"": "This is a command to have Taqwa—to be conscious of Allah, to fear His punishment, to hope for His mercy, and to live a life of obedience to Him. Being mindful of Allah means remembering Him in every action, avoiding what He has forbidden, and doing what He has commanded. It is like a child who behaves well because they know their loving parent is watching—not out of terror, but out of respect, love, and awareness."
  },
  3: {
    "He created the heavens and the earth for a purpose.": "Allah did not create this magnificent universe as a random accident or for mere entertainment. Everything was created with truth, wisdom, and a divine purpose. The heavens with their stars, galaxies, and vastness, and the earth with its mountains, oceans, and life—all of it points to a Creator who designed it for a reason. That reason includes testing humanity, allowing us to worship Him, and ultimately bringing us to account. As Allah says elsewhere: \"Did you think that We created you in vain and that you would not be returned to Us?\" (Qur'an 23:115). The purpose gives meaning to our existence.",
    "Exalted is He above what they associate with Him ˹in worship˺!": "Again, Allah emphasizes His transcendence above all false gods. The One who created such an incredible universe—with perfect balance, laws of physics, ecosystems, and beauty—cannot possibly have partners or equals. The idols people worship have created nothing. They cannot even create a fly. So how can they be compared to the Almighty Creator? This repetition throughout the surah drives home the absurdity of shirk."
  },
  4: {
    "He created humans from a sperm-drop,": "Allah reminds humanity of their humble origin. Every human being, no matter how powerful, wealthy, or arrogant, began as a tiny, insignificant drop of fluid. This is a fact of biology that the Qur'an stated over 1400 years ago. It is meant to humble us and make us reflect on our Creator. We were nothing, and Allah brought us into existence, gave us form, intellect, and abilities. How can such a creature then turn around and deny or challenge its Creator?",
    "then—behold!—they openly challenge ˹Him˺.": "Despite this humble beginning, humans have the audacity to argue against Allah, deny His existence, reject His messengers, and dispute His signs. The Arabic word \"khaSeem\" means a fierce, open opponent in argument. It is astonishing that the very creature who was created from something so lowly would then stand up and argue against the One who gave him life, speech, and intellect. This describes the behavior of the arrogant disbelievers who debated with the Prophet about resurrection, God's existence, and the truth of Islam. It is a reminder that pride and arrogance are completely unfounded when we remember where we came from."
  },
  5: {
    "And He created the cattle for you": "Allah created animals like camels, cows, sheep, and goats specifically for the service of human beings. This is a direct blessing from Allah, designed to make human life easier and more comfortable. These animals did not evolve randomly to serve us—they were intentionally created by Allah as a mercy.",
    "as a source of warmth,": "From their wool, fur, and hides, humans make clothing, blankets, tents, and coverings that protect from cold weather. In ancient times and even today in many parts of the world, animal products are essential for survival in harsh climates.",
    "food,": "These animals provide meat, milk, cheese, and other dairy products that nourish human beings. They are a halal (permissible) source of protein and sustenance that Allah has provided.",
    "and ˹many other˺ benefits.": "Beyond warmth and food, cattle provide leather for shoes and bags, bones for tools, and even their waste can be used as fertilizer or fuel. Every part of the animal has a use, showing Allah's perfect design and generosity."
  },
  6: {
    "They are also pleasing to you when you bring them home": "There is a sense of beauty, pride, and satisfaction when a shepherd or farmer brings their animals home in the evening. Watching healthy, well-fed cattle returning gives a feeling of blessing and accomplishment. This aesthetic pleasure is also a gift from Allah.",
    "and when you take them out to graze.": "Similarly, in the morning, when the animals go out to pasture, there is beauty in watching them move across the landscape. Allah acknowledges that humans find joy and peace in such scenes. It is not just about utility—Allah wants us to find happiness and beauty in His creation."
  },
  7: {
    "And they carry your loads to ˹distant˺ lands": "Camels, donkeys, and other beasts of burden carry heavy goods across vast distances for trade, migration, and travel. In the time of the Prophet (peace be upon him), caravans would travel from Makkah to Syria and Yemen carrying merchandise. This transportation system was built on the backs of these animals.",
    "which you could not otherwise reach without great hardship.": "Without these animals, humans would have to carry heavy loads themselves across deserts, mountains, and difficult terrain. This would be exhausting, dangerous, and often impossible. Allah made these animals strong and capable of bearing burdens that humans cannot, and He subjected them to human control as a mercy.",
    "Surely your Lord is Ever Gracious, Most Merciful.": "This verse concludes by reminding us of Allah's nature. He is Rauf (Ever Gracious, Compassionate) and Raheem (Most Merciful). All these blessings—the animals, their uses, the ease they bring—are manifestations of Allah's kindness and care for His servants. He did not leave us to struggle alone but provided everything we need."
  },
  8: {
    "˹He also created˺ horses, mules, and donkeys for your transportation": "In addition to cattle, Allah created these animals specifically for riding and travel. Horses are known for their speed and strength, mules for their endurance, and donkeys for their ability to navigate difficult paths. Each animal has unique qualities suited for different needs.",
    "and adornment.": "Beyond practical use, these animals are also beautiful. Horses, in particular, are admired for their elegance, grace, and majesty. Owning fine horses was a symbol of honor and status in Arab culture. Allah acknowledges this aesthetic dimension—He created beauty for us to enjoy, not just utility.",
    "And He creates what you do not know.": "This is a profound statement. Allah is telling us that His creation is not limited to what we see or know. There are creatures, inventions, and forms of transportation that future generations will discover. Today we have cars, planes, and trains—things the Arabs of that time could never have imagined. And still, there are things yet to be discovered. This shows the timeless nature of the Qur'an and the limitless power of Allah."
  },
  9: {
    "It is upon Allah ˹alone˺ to ˹clearly˺ show the Straight Way.": "Allah has taken it upon Himself, out of His mercy, to clarify the path that leads to Him, to Paradise, and to success in this life and the next. He does not leave humanity wandering without guidance. He sent prophets, revealed books, and made the truth clear. The \"Straight Way\" is Islam—submission to Allah alone, following His commands, and avoiding His prohibitions. Allah says: \"Indeed, this Qur'an guides to that which is most suitable\" (Qur'an 17:9).",
    "Other ways are deviant.": "Any path that deviates from what Allah has revealed is crooked and leads astray. Whether it is the worship of idols, following desires, or inventing new religions—all of these are deviant paths that lead away from Allah. There is only one straight path, but there are countless wrong paths. The Prophet (peace be upon him) once drew a straight line and said, \"This is the path of Allah,\" then drew lines branching off from it and said, \"These are other paths, and on each path is a devil calling to it.\"",
    "Had He willed, He would have easily imposed guidance upon all of you.": "Allah has the power to make every single person a believer. He could have created humans without free will, like angels who obey without question. But that is not the test. Allah gave humans the ability to choose so that faith would be meaningful. Those who choose to believe, despite the temptations and challenges, are rewarded. Those who choose to disbelieve bear the consequences of their choice. This life is a test of free will."
  },
  10: {
    "He is the One Who sends down rain from the sky,": "Allah alone controls the rain. No human, idol, or force of nature can make it rain. The water cycle—evaporation, cloud formation, and precipitation—all happens by Allah's command. This water is the source of all life on earth. Without it, nothing would survive.",
    "from which you drink": "The most basic human need is water. Allah provides fresh, clean water from the sky that fills rivers, wells, and reservoirs. This is a direct blessing that we often take for granted. In many parts of the world, people struggle for water, and this verse reminds us to be grateful for every sip we take.",
    "and by which plants grow for your cattle to graze.": "The same rain that provides drinking water also causes vegetation to grow. This vegetation feeds the livestock that we depend on for food, clothing, and transportation. It is a complete, interconnected system designed by Allah to sustain life."
  },
  11: {
    "With it He produces for you ˹various˺ crops, olives, palm trees, grapevines,": "From the same water, Allah produces an incredible variety of plants and trees. Crops like wheat and barley for bread, olives for oil, date palms for fruit and countless uses, and grapevines for fruit and other products. Each of these plants has different colors, tastes, textures, and benefits—all from the same water and soil. This diversity is a sign of Allah's creative power.",
    "and every type of fruit.": "Beyond the ones mentioned, Allah produces countless types of fruits around the world—apples, oranges, mangoes, bananas, berries, and more. Each region has its own unique produce, suited to its climate and people. This abundance is a mercy from Allah.",
    "Surely in this is a sign for those who reflect.": "For people who think deeply, these blessings are not random. They point to a Creator who is wise, generous, and purposeful. A single seed, water, and soil combine to produce a tree that gives fruit for decades. How can this be an accident? Those who reflect (yatafakkarun) will recognize Allah's signs and be grateful."
  },
  12: {
    "And He has subjected for your benefit the day and the night,": "Allah has made the alternation of day and night serve human purposes. The day is for work, activity, and earning a livelihood. The night is for rest, sleep, and recovery. This rhythm is perfectly suited to human biology and needs. Without this cycle, life would be unbearable.",
    "the sun and the moon.": "The sun provides light, heat, and energy that makes life possible. The moon provides light at night, controls the tides, and helps mark the passage of months. Both are precisely positioned and move in exact orbits. If the sun were closer, we would burn; if farther, we would freeze. All of this is by Allah's perfect design.",
    "And the stars have been subjected by His command.": "The countless stars in the sky are also under Allah's control. They are used for navigation, for beauty, and as signs of Allah's majesty. Ancient travelers used stars to find their way across deserts and oceans. Despite their immense size and distance, they all obey Allah's command.",
    "Surely in this are signs for those who understand.": "People of intellect (ya'qiloon) will see these cosmic phenomena not as random events but as clear signs of a Creator. The precision of planetary orbits, the reliability of sunrise and sunset, the predictability of lunar phases—all of these point to intelligent design, not chance."
  },
  13: {
    "And ˹He subjected˺ for you whatever He has created on earth of varying colours.": "Look around at the incredible diversity on earth—animals of different species and colors, plants of countless varieties, minerals and gems of various hues, landscapes of different textures. All of this variety serves purposes: beauty, utility, medicine, food, and more. The fact that everything is not the same color or type shows Allah's creative wisdom. Imagine if everything were one color—how dull and limited life would be!",
    "Surely in this is a sign for those who are mindful.": "Those who remember Allah (yathdhakkarun) and are mindful of His blessings will see every color, every creature, and every creation as a reminder of Him. A rainbow, a colorful bird, a vibrant flower—all of these are opportunities to remember and thank Allah."
  },
  14: {
    "And He is the One Who has subjected the sea,": "The vast oceans, which could easily overwhelm and destroy humanity, have been made subservient to human use by Allah's command. We can sail on them, fish in them, and extract resources from them—all because Allah has made this possible.",
    "so from it you may eat tender seafood": "The sea provides fresh fish, shrimp, and other seafood that is delicious and nutritious. This is halal sustenance that Allah has made abundant in the oceans. Millions of people around the world depend on the sea for their food.",
    "and extract ornaments to wear.": "From the sea come pearls, coral, and other precious materials used for jewelry and decoration. These treasures from the depths of the ocean are gifts from Allah for human enjoyment and beautification.",
    "And you see the ships ploughing their way through it,": "Ships cutting through the waves, carrying passengers and cargo across vast distances, are a remarkable sight. The ability to build vessels that float and navigate the seas is a blessing from Allah. Maritime trade has connected civilizations throughout history.",
    "so you may seek His bounty": "The sea is a means of seeking Allah's provision through trade, fishing, and exploration. People travel across oceans to find opportunities, exchange goods, and build connections—all part of seeking Allah's bounty.",
    "and give thanks ˹to Him˺.": "The ultimate purpose of all these blessings is that we recognize Allah's generosity and express gratitude. Every fish we eat, every journey we make by sea, every pearl we admire should remind us of the One who provided it all."
  },
  15: {
    "He has placed into the earth firm mountains,": "Allah has anchored the earth with massive mountains that stabilize it. Mountains act like pegs or stakes that help keep the earth's crust stable. Modern geology confirms that mountains have deep roots that extend into the earth, providing stability.",
    "so it does not shake with you,": "Without these stabilizing features, the earth would be in constant violent motion, making life impossible. While earthquakes do occur, the overall stability of the earth's surface is maintained by Allah's design. We walk, build, and live on the earth without constantly being thrown about.",
    "as well as rivers,": "Allah also created rivers that flow across the land, providing fresh water for drinking, agriculture, and transportation. Rivers like the Nile, the Euphrates, and the Ganges have sustained civilizations for thousands of years. They are arteries of life on the earth.",
    "and pathways so you may find your way.": "Natural pathways through mountains, valleys, and plains allow humans to travel from place to place. These routes have been used since ancient times for trade, migration, and communication. Allah created the earth with built-in features that facilitate human movement and connection."
  },
  16: {
    "Also by landmarks": "Allah placed recognizable features on the earth—mountains, rock formations, trees, and other markers—that help travelers navigate. Before modern technology, people relied on these landmarks to know where they were and where they were going.",
    "and stars do people find their way.": "The stars have been used for navigation for thousands of years. Sailors crossing oceans and travelers crossing deserts would look to the stars to determine direction. The North Star, for example, has guided countless journeys. This is yet another blessing from Allah, who placed these celestial guides in the sky for human benefit."
  },
  17: {
    "Can the One Who creates be equal to those who do not?": "This is a powerful rhetorical question. Allah, who has created everything mentioned in the previous verses—the heavens, the earth, humans, animals, rain, plants, seas, mountains, stars—can He possibly be compared to idols and false gods who have created nothing? The answer is obvious: absolutely not. The Creator is infinitely superior to anything that is created or cannot create.",
    "Will you not then be mindful?": "Allah appeals to human reason and memory. If people would just stop and think, remember all the blessings around them, and reflect on who is responsible for all of it, they would never worship anything besides Allah. This is a call to use the intellect that Allah gave us to recognize the truth."
  },
  18: {
    "If you tried to count Allah's blessings, you would never be able to number them.": "This verse puts human limitation into perspective. After listing many blessings, Allah tells us that what was mentioned is only a fraction of His favors. Every breath, every heartbeat, every moment of health, every morsel of food, every loving relationship, every ability and opportunity—all are blessings from Allah. If we spent our entire lives counting, we would never finish. This should fill us with humility and gratitude.",
    "Surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Despite our inability to properly thank Allah for all His blessings, and despite our shortcomings and sins, Allah forgives. He knows we are weak and imperfect, and He covers our faults. His mercy extends to those who sincerely try to be grateful, even if they fall short. This gives hope to the believer—we can never thank Him enough, but He forgives us anyway."
  },
  19: {
    "And Allah knows what you conceal and what you reveal.": "Nothing is hidden from Allah. He knows the secrets of every heart, the whispered conversations, the hidden intentions, and the private sins—just as He knows the public actions and spoken words. This is both a warning and a comfort. For the sincere believer, it means Allah sees their hidden struggles and good intentions. For the hypocrite and sinner, it means there is no escape from Allah's knowledge. On the Day of Judgment, everything will be exposed."
  },
  20: {
    "But those ˹idols˺ they invoke besides Allah cannot create anything": "The false gods that people worship—whether idols of stone, wood, or metal, or even misguided concepts—have never created a single thing. They cannot bring anything into existence. They have no power whatsoever.",
    "—they themselves are created.": "Not only can these idols not create, but they themselves are the products of creation. Humans carved them, shaped them, and made them. How can something made by human hands be worthy of worship? How can the creation be equal to the Creator? This exposes the absurdity of idol worship in the clearest terms."
  },
  21: {
    "They are dead, not alive": "These idols have no life, no soul, no consciousness. They cannot hear prayers, respond to requests, or do anything at all. They are lifeless objects. Worshipping them is like talking to a wall and expecting an answer. Allah, in contrast, is Al-Hayy—the Ever-Living, who never dies and is always aware.",
    "—not even knowing when their followers will be resurrected.": "These idols do not even know when the Day of Resurrection will come. They have no knowledge of the unseen, no awareness of the future. They cannot save themselves, let alone save those who worship them. On the Day of Judgment, both the idols and their worshippers will be gathered, and the idols will be of no help whatsoever."
  },
  22: {
    "Your God is ˹only˺ One God.": "After demonstrating the powerlessness of false gods, Allah declares the fundamental truth: there is only One God worthy of worship. He alone created, sustains, and controls everything. This is the central message of Islam—Tawheed, the absolute oneness of Allah. There are no partners, no intermediaries, no equals.",
    "As for those who do not believe in the Hereafter, their hearts are in denial,": "Those who reject the afterlife have hearts that refuse to accept the truth. Even when clear signs are presented, they deny them. Their hearts are sealed because of their persistent rejection. They do not want to believe because belief would require them to change their behavior and be accountable.",
    "and they are too proud.": "At the root of their disbelief is arrogance (kibr). They are too proud to submit to Allah, too proud to follow a prophet, too proud to admit they might be wrong. Pride is a barrier to faith. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"No one who has an atom's weight of arrogance in his heart will enter Paradise.\" This pride prevents them from seeing the obvious truth all around them."
  },
  23: {
    "Without a doubt, Allah knows what they conceal and what they reveal.": "Allah repeats this to emphasize that nothing escapes His knowledge. The arrogant disbelievers may hide their mockery, their plots, and their rejection, but Allah knows everything. Their private meetings, their secret thoughts, their public statements—all are known to Him. They cannot hide from Allah.",
    "He certainly does not like those who are too proud.": "Allah explicitly states His displeasure with arrogance. Pride is one of the most hated characteristics in the sight of Allah because it was the sin of Iblees (Satan), who refused to bow to Adam out of arrogance. Those who are arrogant place themselves above others and refuse to submit to Allah. This leads to their downfall in this world and the next. The believer should always strive for humility, recognizing that all we have is from Allah and that we are servants in need of His mercy."
  },
  24: {
    "And when it is said to them, \"What has your Lord revealed?\"": "When the disbelievers of Makkah were asked about the Qur'an and the message brought by Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him), they were given an opportunity to acknowledge the truth. This question was posed by visitors, pilgrims, or those genuinely curious about the new revelation. It was a chance for them to reflect and respond honestly.",
    "They say, \"Ancient fables!\"": "Instead of recognizing the Qur'an as divine guidance, they dismissed it as old stories and legends from the past—myths and tales of ancient peoples with no relevance or truth. This was their arrogant way of rejecting the message without even considering its content. They compared the Qur'an to folklore to discourage others from listening. This is a tactic still used today—dismissing religious truth as outdated or irrelevant without genuine engagement with its message."
  },
  25: {
    "Let them bear their burdens in full on the Day of Judgment": "These disbelievers will carry the complete weight of their own sins on the Day of Resurrection. Nothing will be reduced or forgiven because they rejected the truth knowingly. Every act of mockery, every denial, and every sin will be accounted for.",
    "as well as some of the burdens of those they mislead without knowledge.": "Even worse, they will also carry a portion of the sins of those they led astray. When someone spreads misguidance, they become responsible not only for their own disbelief but also for influencing others to disbelieve. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Whoever starts a bad practice will bear its sin and the sin of everyone who acts upon it without that decreasing their sins in the least.\" (Sahih Muslim). Those who were misled still bear their own sins, but the leaders of misguidance have an additional burden.",
    "Evil indeed is what they will bear!": "This is Allah's condemnation of their burden. What a terrible load they will carry—the combined weight of personal sins plus the sins of those they corrupted. It is a warning to anyone who spreads falsehood or discourages others from the truth."
  },
  26: {
    "Indeed, those before them had plotted,": "The disbelievers of Makkah were not the first to scheme against Allah's message. Previous nations—like the people of Pharaoh, the people of Nimrod, and others—also made elaborate plans to oppose the truth and harm the messengers. They thought their power, wealth, and strategies would protect them.",
    "but Allah struck at the ˹very˺ foundation of their structure,": "Allah did not just weaken their plans—He destroyed the very foundation upon which they built their power. This is a metaphor for how Allah undermines the core of their strength. Just like a building whose foundation is removed, everything they built collapsed completely.",
    "so the roof collapsed on top of them,": "Their own constructions—literal or metaphorical—fell upon them. The very things they trusted for protection became the means of their destruction. This is a powerful image of divine justice: their plots backfired, and they were buried under their own schemes.",
    "and the torment came upon them from where they did not expect.": "Allah's punishment came from directions they never anticipated. They felt secure, but security was an illusion. This teaches that no one can outsmart Allah or escape His decree. He can bring punishment from any direction, at any time, in ways humans cannot predict."
  },
  27: {
    "Then on the Day of Judgment He will humiliate them": "After their destruction in this world, they will face further humiliation on the Day of Resurrection. They will be disgraced in front of all of creation. The pride they had in this life will turn into shame and regret.",
    "and say, \"Where are My ˹so-called˺ associate-gods for whose sake you used to oppose ˹the believers˺?\"": "Allah will question them about the false gods they worshipped and fought for. Where are those idols now? Where are the partners you claimed for Allah? They cannot help you today. This question is not for information—Allah knows everything—but to expose their foolishness and compound their shame. They opposed the believers, persecuted the prophets, and rejected the truth for the sake of false gods that are now utterly useless.",
    "Those gifted with knowledge will say, \"Surely disgrace and misery today are upon the disbelievers.\"": "The people of knowledge—the prophets, scholars, angels, or righteous believers—will declare the obvious truth: today, all disgrace and suffering belong to those who disbelieved. The tables have turned. In this world, disbelievers may have had power and status, but on this Day, they have nothing but humiliation."
  },
  28: {
    "Those whose souls the angels seize while they wrong themselves": "This describes the moment of death for the disbelievers. The angels come to take their souls while they are in a state of wrongdoing—meaning they died without repentance, persisting in their disbelief and sins. They wronged themselves by choosing a path that led to their own destruction.",
    "will then offer ˹full˺ submission ˹and say falsely,˺ \"We did not do any evil.\"": "At the moment of death, when they see the angels and realize the truth, they suddenly become submissive and humble. They lie and claim innocence, saying they never did anything wrong. This is a desperate attempt to escape punishment, but it is too late. In this world, they were arrogant; now they are groveling and lying.",
    "˹The angels will say,˺ \"No! Surely Allah fully knows what you used to do.": "The angels reject their lies completely. Allah has perfect knowledge of everything they did—every sin, every act of disbelief, every moment of arrogance. Nothing is hidden from Him. Their denial is useless because the record of their deeds is complete."
  },
  29: {
    "So enter the gates of Hell, to stay there forever.": "After their lies are exposed, they are commanded to enter Hell through its gates—and there are multiple gates, each for different categories of sinners. They will remain there eternally, with no escape and no end to their suffering.",
    "Indeed, what an evil home for the arrogant!": "Hell is described as the worst possible dwelling, specifically designated for those who were arrogant. Their pride in this world, their refusal to submit to Allah, and their mockery of the truth have led them to this terrible destination. Arrogance is a direct cause of entering Hell, as the Prophet (peace be upon him) warned about even an atom's weight of pride preventing entry to Paradise."
  },
  30: {
    "And ˹when˺ it is said to those mindful ˹of Allah˺, \"What has your Lord revealed?\"": "In contrast to the arrogant disbelievers, when the believers—those who have taqwa (mindfulness of Allah)—are asked the same question about what Allah has revealed, their response is completely different. They approach the question with sincerity and gratitude.",
    "They say, \"All the best!\"": "The believers recognize the Qur'an as pure goodness, guidance, mercy, and light. Instead of dismissing it as fables, they embrace it as the best thing that could ever be revealed. This shows the difference between a heart that is open to truth and one that is sealed by arrogance.",
    "For those who do good in this world, there is goodness.": "Those who believe and do righteous deeds will receive good in this world—blessings, peace of heart, provision, and protection from Allah. Good actions bring good results even in this life.",
    "But far better is the ˹eternal˺ Home of the Hereafter.": "As good as this world can be for believers, the Hereafter is incomparably better. The pleasures of Paradise are eternal and perfect, while the blessings of this world are temporary and mixed with hardships.",
    "How excellent indeed is the home of the righteous:": "Allah praises the final destination of the righteous, emphasizing how wonderful it will be. This is encouragement for believers to remain steadfast, knowing that their ultimate home will be amazing beyond imagination."
  },
  31: {
    "the Gardens of Eternity which they will enter,": "These are the gardens of eternal residence—Jannaat 'Adn—permanent homes in Paradise where the believers will live forever. Unlike worldly homes that decay and are eventually left behind, these gardens are everlasting.",
    "under which rivers flow.": "Rivers will flow beneath the gardens and palaces of Paradise—rivers of water, milk, honey, and wine (which does not intoxicate). This imagery represents abundance, beauty, and endless refreshment.",
    "In it they will have whatever they desire.": "Whatever the inhabitants of Paradise wish for, they will have. There will be no unmet needs, no unfulfilled desires, no waiting or disappointment. This is the ultimate satisfaction and happiness.",
    "This is how Allah rewards the righteous—": "This magnificent reward is Allah's payment to those who had taqwa—who were conscious of Him, obeyed Him, and avoided what He prohibited. Allah rewards generously, far beyond what anyone could earn or deserve."
  },
  32: {
    "those whose souls the angels take while they are virtuous,": "In beautiful contrast to the death of disbelievers (verse 28), the righteous die in a state of purity and goodness. Their souls are taken gently by the angels while they are in a state pleasing to Allah. The Prophet (peace be upon him) described how the angels of mercy come to the believer at death with white silk and fragrance.",
    "saying ˹to them˺, \"Peace be upon you!": "The angels greet the righteous with salaam—peace. This is a greeting of honor, comfort, and good news. At the most significant moment of transition—death—the believer is welcomed with peace.",
    "Enter Paradise for what you used to do.\"": "The angels give them the glad tidings of Paradise as a reward for their righteous deeds. Their good actions in this world—prayers, charity, patience, kindness, obedience—have led to this beautiful ending. This is the best farewell anyone could receive."
  },
  33: {
    "Are they only awaiting the coming of the angels or the command of your Lord ˹O Prophet˺?": "What are these disbelievers waiting for? Are they waiting until the angels of death come to take their souls, or until Allah's command of punishment descends upon them? By then, it will be too late for repentance or faith. This is a rhetorical question meant to shake them from their complacency.",
    "So were those before them.": "This pattern is not new. Previous generations of disbelievers also delayed, denied, and waited until punishment came. The people of Noah, 'Aad, Thamud, and others all did the same—and they were all destroyed.",
    "And Allah never wronged them,": "Allah is absolutely just. He does not punish anyone unfairly. Every person receives clear warnings and ample opportunity to repent and believe.",
    "but it was they who wronged themselves.": "The destruction they faced was entirely their own fault. They chose disbelief, they chose arrogance, they chose to reject the truth. Allah simply gave them the consequences of their choices. This is a crucial principle: humans have free will, and they bear responsibility for their decisions."
  },
  34: {
    "Then the evil ˹consequences˺ of their deeds overtook them,": "The bad results of their actions caught up with them. Every sin has consequences, and eventually, those consequences manifest. In this world or the next, evil deeds produce evil results.",
    "and they were overwhelmed by what they used to ridicule.": "The very punishment they mocked and laughed at became their reality. They joked about the Day of Judgment, they ridiculed warnings of Hellfire, they made fun of the prophets—and then that punishment surrounded them from all sides. This is a sobering reminder that what we dismiss or mock may become our reality."
  },
  35: {
    "The polytheists argue, \"Had Allah willed, neither we nor our forefathers would have worshipped anything other than Him, nor prohibited anything without His command.\"": "The polytheists tried to justify their idol worship by blaming Allah. They argued: \"If Allah didn't want us to worship idols, He would have stopped us. Since He didn't stop us, He must approve.\" This is a twisted use of the concept of divine will (qadar) to escape accountability. Yes, everything happens by Allah's permission, but that does not remove human responsibility. Allah gave humans free will and the ability to choose. He sent messengers to guide them. Their choice to worship idols was their own, and they will be held accountable for it.",
    "So did those before them.": "Previous nations made the same flawed argument. They tried to blame Allah for their sins instead of accepting responsibility. It is an old excuse that has never been accepted.",
    "Is not the messengers' duty only to deliver ˹the message˺ clearly?": "Allah clarifies that the messengers' role is to convey the message clearly—not to force anyone to believe. The Prophet (peace be upon him) delivered the truth; what people do with it is their choice. On the Day of Judgment, no one can say they were not warned."
  },
  36: {
    "We surely sent a messenger to every community, saying, \"Worship Allah and shun false gods.\"": "Allah's justice is complete. He did not leave any nation without guidance. Every community throughout history received a messenger with the same core message: worship Allah alone and avoid all false gods (taghut). No one can claim ignorance because Allah sent guidance to everyone.",
    "But some of them were guided by Allah,": "Among every nation, there were those who accepted the truth and were guided. Allah facilitated their guidance because they sincerely sought it and were humble enough to accept it.",
    "while others were destined to stray.": "Others, due to their arrogance and rejection, were left in their misguidance. Allah does not guide those who do not want guidance. When people persistently reject the truth, Allah allows them to remain astray as a consequence of their choice.",
    "So travel throughout the land and see the fate of the deniers!": "Allah invites people to travel and observe the ruins of previous civilizations—the destroyed cities, the fallen empires, the evidence of past punishments. The ruins of 'Aad, Thamud, Sodom, and Pharaoh's people still exist as lessons. Those who denied the messengers were destroyed, and their remains testify to the truth of Allah's warnings."
  },
  37: {
    "Even though you ˹O Prophet˺ are keen on their guidance,": "The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) desperately wanted his people to be guided. He loved them and wanted to save them from Hell. His concern was so deep that Allah had to console him multiple times in the Qur'an not to grieve too much over those who refused to believe.",
    "Allah certainly does not guide those He leaves to stray,": "Despite the Prophet's earnest desire, guidance is ultimately from Allah. When someone persistently rejects the truth and chooses misguidance, Allah leaves them in that state. The Prophet cannot force anyone to believe—he can only deliver the message.",
    "and they will have no helpers.": "Those whom Allah leaves in misguidance will find no one to help them. No intercessor, no protector, no savior will come to their aid. They chose to reject Allah, and on the Day of Judgment, they will face the consequences alone."
  },
  38: {
    "They swear by Allah their most solemn oaths that Allah will never raise the dead to life.": "The disbelievers made emphatic oaths—swearing by Allah Himself—that resurrection would never happen. They were absolutely convinced that death was the end. This shows their complete denial of the afterlife, despite ironically invoking Allah's name in their oaths.",
    "Yes ˹He will˺! It is a true promise binding on Him,": "Allah responds with absolute certainty: Yes, resurrection will happen! It is a promise that Allah has made, and He never breaks His promises. The One who created humans from nothing the first time can certainly bring them back to life.",
    "but most people do not know.": "Most people are ignorant of this reality. They live as if there is no afterlife, as if their actions have no consequences beyond this world. But their ignorance does not change the truth."
  },
  39: {
    "˹He will do that˺ to make clear to them what they disagreed on,": "One purpose of resurrection is to resolve all disputes. In this world, people disagree about God, religion, right and wrong, and the afterlife. On the Day of Judgment, all truth will be made clear. There will be no more debate—everyone will see the reality.",
    "and for the disbelievers to know that they were liars.": "The disbelievers will finally realize that they were wrong. They lied to themselves and others about there being no resurrection, no judgment, no accountability. On that Day, their lies will be exposed, and they will face the truth they denied."
  },
  40: {
    "If We ever will something ˹to exist˺, all We say is: \"Be!\" And it is!": "This verse demonstrates Allah's absolute power. When Allah decides something should happen, He simply commands \"Kun\" (Be), and it comes into existence immediately. He does not need tools, time, or effort. Creating the universe, resurrecting all of humanity, bringing about the Day of Judgment—all of these are effortless for Allah. This makes the resurrection not only possible but easy for Him."
  },
  41: {
    "As for those who emigrated in ˹the cause of˺ Allah after being persecuted,": "This verse honors the early Muslims who left their homes, families, wealth, and everything familiar for the sake of Allah. They were persecuted in Makkah—tortured, boycotted, and oppressed—and then made the difficult decision to emigrate, first to Abyssinia and later to Madinah. This sacrifice is immense and Allah acknowledges it.",
    "We will surely bless them with a good home in this world.": "Allah promises these emigrants a good settlement in this world. The Muhajirun (emigrants) were eventually given homes, security, and honor in Madinah. After years of persecution, they found peace and community. This is Allah's reward for their sacrifice even in this life.",
    "But the reward of the Hereafter is far better, if only they knew.": "As good as the worldly reward is, the reward of the Hereafter is incomparably greater. Those who sacrifice for Allah will receive eternal bliss in Paradise. If people truly understood how great that reward is, they would eagerly make any sacrifice."
  },
  42: {
    "˹It is˺ they who have patiently endured,": "These emigrants are characterized by sabr—patient endurance. They faced persecution with patience, they endured the hardship of leaving home with patience, and they waited for Allah's victory with patience. Patience is one of the highest virtues in Islam and is essential for anyone facing trials.",
    "and in their Lord they put their trust.": "Along with patience, they had tawakkul—complete trust and reliance on Allah. They did not know exactly how things would turn out, but they trusted that Allah would take care of them. This combination of patience and trust is the formula for navigating life's challenges as a believer."
  },
  43: {
    "We did not send ˹messengers˺ before you ˹O Prophet˺ except mere men inspired by Us.": "One objection the polytheists raised was: \"Why is this messenger a human being like us? Why didn't Allah send an angel?\" Allah responds that all previous messengers were also human men who received revelation. This is Allah's wisdom—humans can best relate to and learn from other humans. A human messenger eats, sleeps, faces challenges, and demonstrates how to live righteously in practical terms.",
    "If you ˹polytheists˺ do not know ˹this already˺, then ask those who have knowledge ˹of the Scriptures˺.": "If the polytheists are unsure about this, they should ask the People of the Scripture—Jews and Christians who have knowledge of previous revelations. They will confirm that Moses, Jesus, David, and all prophets were human beings, not angels. This is an appeal to historical evidence and existing religious knowledge."
  },
  44: {
    "˹We sent them˺ with clear proofs and divine Books.": "The messengers were not sent empty-handed. They came with bayyinaat (clear proofs, miracles, and evidence) and zubur (divine scriptures). They had proof of their truthfulness and guidance for their communities.",
    "And We have sent down to you ˹O Prophet˺ the Reminder,": "The Qur'an is called \"the Reminder\" (al-Dhikr) because it reminds humanity of their purpose, their Creator, and their ultimate destination. It reminds people of what their fitrah (natural disposition) already knows but may have forgotten.",
    "so that you may explain to people what has been revealed for them,": "The Prophet's role is to explain and clarify the Qur'an to people. His teachings, actions, and statements (the Sunnah) are essential for understanding how to implement the Qur'an in daily life. This is why following the Prophet's example is obligatory for Muslims.",
    "and perhaps they will reflect.": "The goal is that people will think deeply and contemplate the message. The Qur'an is not meant to be recited without understanding—it is meant to transform hearts and minds. Reflection leads to faith, action, and ultimately salvation."
  },
  45: {
    "Do those who devise evil plots feel secure that Allah will not cause the earth to swallow them?": "Those who scheme against Islam and plot evil should not feel safe. Allah can cause the earth to open up and swallow them, as He did with Qarun (Korah), who was arrogant about his wealth and was swallowed by the earth (Qur'an 28:81). This punishment can come suddenly and completely.",
    "Or that the torment will not come upon them in ways they cannot comprehend?": "Allah's punishment can come in forms that humans cannot predict or understand. It might be a natural disaster, a disease, an economic collapse, or something completely unexpected. The point is that no one can feel secure from Allah's plan."
  },
  46: {
    "Or that He will not seize them while they go about ˹their day˺,": "Allah might seize them while they are busy with their daily activities—traveling, working, trading, or enjoying life. They might be in the middle of their routine when sudden death or calamity strikes.",
    "for then they will have no escape?": "When Allah decides to punish, no one can escape. There is no running, no hiding, no defense against Allah's decree. Human beings cannot outrun or outsmart the Creator of the universe."
  },
  47: {
    "Or that He will not destroy them gradually?": "Another form of punishment is gradual destruction—slowly losing health, wealth, power, or blessings over time. Sometimes people are destroyed bit by bit, giving them chances to repent, but they remain heedless until it is too late.",
    "But your Lord is truly Ever Gracious, Most Merciful.": "Despite all these warnings, Allah emphasizes His mercy. He is Ra'uf (Ever Gracious) and Raheem (Most Merciful). He does not rush to punish; He gives time for repentance. He sends warnings through messengers. His mercy precedes His wrath. This should motivate people to turn back to Him before it is too late."
  },
  48: {
    "Have they not considered how the shadows of everything Allah has created incline to the right and the left ˹as the sun moves˺,": "Allah draws attention to a simple, observable phenomenon: shadows move throughout the day as the sun moves across the sky. In the morning, shadows stretch one way; in the evening, they stretch the other way. This constant movement is a daily occurrence that most people ignore, but it contains a profound lesson.",
    "totally submitting to Allah in all humility?": "Even the shadows prostrate to Allah! This is a form of submission that all of creation exhibits. Whether they have consciousness or not, everything in the universe obeys Allah's laws and submits to His will. The sun rises and sets on schedule, the earth rotates, the seasons change—all in perfect obedience. Yet some humans, who have been given intellect and choice, refuse to submit to the One to whom all creation bows."
  },
  49: {
    "And to Allah ˹alone˺ bows down ˹in submission˺ whatever is in the heavens and whatever is on the earth of living creatures,": "Every living thing in existence—in the heavens and on the earth—prostrates to Allah. This includes animals, insects, birds, fish, and all creatures. Each creation has its own way of glorifying and submitting to Allah, even if we do not perceive it. Allah says elsewhere: \"There is not a thing except that it celebrates His praise, but you do not understand their way of glorification\" (Qur'an 17:44).",
    "as do the angels—who are not too proud ˹to do so˺.": "Even the angels, despite their exalted status and closeness to Allah, prostrate to Him without any pride. They never consider themselves too great to worship. If the magnificent angels, who are made of light and have no sinful inclinations, submit completely to Allah, how can any human being be too proud to do the same?"
  },
  50: {
    "They fear their Lord above them,": "The angels and all obedient creatures fear Allah, who is above all creation in His majesty and power. This fear is not the terror of a victim before an oppressor, but the reverent awe of servants before an All-Mighty, All-Wise Master. They recognize Allah's greatness and their own insignificance before Him.",
    "and do whatever they are commanded.": "They obey Allah's commands completely and immediately. There is no hesitation, no argument, no selective obedience. Whatever Allah orders, they do. This is the model of true submission. The angels are presented as examples for humans—we should also fear Allah, worship Him without arrogance, and obey His commands fully."
  },
  51: {
    "And Allah has said, \"Do not take two gods.": "Allah directly prohibits the worship of multiple gods. Even two gods is too many—let alone the hundreds or thousands that various cultures have invented. The concept of multiple deities implies competition, conflict, and imperfection among them. But Allah is One, without any rival or partner. This command cuts to the heart of shirk (associating partners with Allah), which is the greatest sin.",
    "There is only One God.": "This is the fundamental declaration of Islamic monotheism (Tawheed). There is absolutely only One God—One Creator, One Sustainer, One who deserves worship. This truth is simple, logical, and self-evident when one reflects on the universe. Multiple creators would lead to chaos; one unified Creator explains the order and harmony we observe.",
    "So be in awe of Me ˹alone˺.\"": "Since there is only One God, fear, reverence, and awe should be directed to Him alone. The Arabic word \"rahbah\" implies a sense of fearful respect that motivates obedience. We should fear displeasing Allah, fear His punishment, and stand in awe of His majesty. No idol, no human, no force of nature deserves this fear—only Allah."
  },
  52: {
    "To Him belongs whatever is in the heavens and the earth,": "Everything in existence belongs to Allah. The stars, planets, galaxies, and all celestial bodies—as well as the earth with all its creatures, resources, and treasures—are His property. He owns it all because He created it all. No one else has any claim to ownership compared to Him.",
    "and to Him ˹alone˺ is the everlasting devotion.": "True, sincere, and permanent devotion belongs only to Allah. Other objects of worship come and go—idols break, kings die, ideologies fade—but Allah remains forever, and worship of Him is the only constant, eternal truth. Religion (deen) in its purest form has always been submission to Allah alone.",
    "Will you then fear any other than Allah?": "This is a rhetorical question that challenges the listener. Given that Allah owns everything and deserves all worship, why would anyone fear anything else? Why fear idols that cannot help or harm? Why fear humans who cannot even control their own lives? Fearing anything besides Allah is irrational and misplaced."
  },
  53: {
    "Whatever blessings you have are from Allah.": "Every single blessing in your life—your health, your wealth, your family, your abilities, the air you breathe, the food you eat—all of it comes from Allah. Humans often attribute their success to their own efforts, intelligence, or luck, but the reality is that Allah is the source of all good. Without His permission and provision, we would have nothing.",
    "Then whenever hardship touches you, to Him ˹alone˺ you cry ˹for help˺.": "When calamity strikes—illness, poverty, danger, or any difficulty—humans instinctively turn to Allah. Even those who claim not to believe often find themselves calling out to a higher power in desperate moments. This is the natural human inclination (fitrah). A person drowning at sea or facing death does not call upon idols—they cry out to the One true God. This proves that deep down, everyone knows Allah is the only real source of help."
  },
  54: {
    "Then as soon as He removes the hardship from you,": "When Allah answers their prayers and relieves their suffering, something strange happens. The danger passes, health returns, the problem is solved—and suddenly they forget who helped them.",
    "a group of you associates ˹others˺ with their Lord ˹in worship˺,": "A portion of people return to their old ways of shirk. They go back to attributing their blessings to idols, luck, or other false causes. They forget that it was Allah who saved them. This is the height of ingratitude—to receive help from Allah and then worship something else. It is like a drowning man who is saved and then thanks the ocean for his rescue instead of the lifeguard."
  },
  55: {
    "only returning Our favours with ingratitude.": "Their response to Allah's blessings is kufr (ingratitude/disbelief). Instead of thanking Allah for His mercy, they deny His role and give credit to others. This is deeply offensive—imagine giving someone a gift and having them thank someone else in front of you.",
    "So enjoy yourselves, for you will soon know.": "This is a stern warning disguised as permission. Allah tells them to go ahead and enjoy their temporary pleasures if they wish—but they should know that consequences are coming. Their enjoyment is short-lived; accountability is certain. This type of warning appears multiple times in the Qur'an, emphasizing that worldly enjoyment without faith leads to ultimate regret."
  },
  56: {
    "And they ˹even˺ assign to those ˹idols˺—who know nothing—a share of what We have provided for them.": "The polytheists would dedicate a portion of their crops, livestock, and wealth to their idols. They would say, \"This portion is for our gods.\" But these idols know nothing—they are lifeless objects without awareness, hearing, or understanding. Meanwhile, Allah is the One who actually provided the crops, the livestock, and the wealth in the first place. So they take what Allah gave them and offer it to things that cannot even perceive the offering. This is complete foolishness.",
    "By Allah! You will certainly be questioned about whatever ˹lies˺ you used to fabricate ˹against Allah˺.": "Allah swears by Himself—the most serious oath—that they will be held accountable for their lies. They invented false religions, fabricated stories about gods, and made up rituals that Allah never authorized. Every lie they told about Allah and His religion will be questioned on the Day of Judgment. This is a warning to anyone who invents things in religion without divine authority."
  },
  57: {
    "And they attribute ˹angels as˺ daughters to Allah—glory be to Him!—": "Some Arab polytheists believed that the angels were daughters of Allah. This belief was doubly wrong: first, Allah does not have children at all—He is above such human characteristics; second, they assigned to Allah what they themselves considered inferior. \"Glory be to Him\" (Subhanahu) is an exclamation rejecting this blasphemy and declaring Allah's absolute perfection and transcendence above such claims.",
    "the opposite of what they desire for themselves.": "These same people who attributed daughters to Allah preferred sons for themselves. They considered daughters to be a burden and a source of shame. So they gave Allah what they despised while keeping what they valued for themselves. This reveals the inconsistency and disrespect in their beliefs."
  },
  58: {
    "Whenever one of them is given the good news of a baby girl,": "When news came that a baby girl was born, instead of joy, there was distress. The Qur'an sarcastically calls it \"good news\" (bushra) because that is what it should be—the birth of any child is a blessing. But their corrupted culture saw it differently.",
    "his face grows gloomy, as he suppresses his rage.": "His face darkens with sadness and anger. He is filled with internal rage but tries to suppress it in front of others. This emotional reaction reveals the deep-seated misogyny of pre-Islamic Arab society. They saw daughters as economic burdens and sources of potential shame, rather than the blessings they truly are."
  },
  59: {
    "He hides himself from the people because of the bad news he has received.": "He is so ashamed that he avoids people. He does not want to face society with the \"disgrace\" of having a daughter. This isolation reflects how twisted their values had become.",
    "Should he keep her in disgrace, or bury her ˹alive˺ in the ground?": "He debates between two terrible options: either keep the daughter and endure lifelong shame, or commit the horrific crime of burying her alive (wa'd). This practice of female infanticide was real in pre-Islamic Arabia. Baby girls were buried alive simply for being female. Islam came to abolish this barbaric practice absolutely.",
    "Evil indeed is their judgment!": "Allah condemns their thinking in the strongest terms. Their judgment—their values, their decision-making, their worldview—is utterly evil. How could they assign to the Almighty Creator what they themselves found shameful? And how could they murder innocent children? This verse is a powerful denunciation of both their theological errors and their moral crimes."
  },
  60: {
    "To those who disbelieve in the Hereafter belong all evil qualities,": "Those who deny the afterlife have the worst attributes—such as attributing children to Allah, killing their daughters, and worshipping idols. Their disbelief in accountability leads to moral corruption. When people do not believe they will answer for their deeds, they commit all kinds of evil.",
    "whereas to Allah belong the finest attributes.": "In contrast, Allah possesses the most perfect and sublime attributes. He is free from all defects, weaknesses, and imperfections that humans attribute to Him. Every beautiful name and quality belongs to Him in the most complete way.",
    "And He is the Almighty, All-Wise.": "Allah is Al-Aziz (The Almighty, The Invincible) and Al-Hakeem (The All-Wise). His power is absolute, and His wisdom is perfect. Everything He does is based on perfect knowledge and wisdom, unlike the foolish judgments of those who reject Him."
  },
  61: {
    "If Allah were to punish people ˹immediately˺ for their wrongdoing, He would not have left a single living being on earth.": "This is a profound statement about Allah's mercy and human sinfulness. If Allah punished every sin instantly and fully, no creature would survive. Everyone commits wrongs—directly or indirectly—and immediate divine justice would wipe out all life. But Allah is merciful; He does not operate that way.",
    "But He delays them for an appointed term.": "Instead, Allah gives people time. This delay is a mercy—an opportunity to repent, to return to Allah, to seek forgiveness, and to change. The term (ajal) is fixed in Allah's knowledge, but unknown to us. This uncertainty should motivate us to use whatever time we have wisely.",
    "And when their time arrives, they cannot delay it for a moment, nor could they advance it.": "When the appointed time comes—whether for an individual's death or for a nation's punishment—there is no negotiation. Not a single moment can be added or subtracted. This emphasizes both Allah's precise control and the urgency of preparing before that moment arrives."
  },
  62: {
    "They attribute to Allah what they hate ˹for themselves˺,": "As mentioned before, they gave Allah what they despised—daughters, while preferring sons for themselves. They also attributed other qualities to Allah that they would find offensive if attributed to themselves. This shows their disrespect for the Divine.",
    "and their tongues utter the lie that they will have the finest reward.": "On top of their false beliefs about Allah, they claimed that even if there was an afterlife, they would receive the best of it. They said things like, \"If there is a Hereafter, we will surely have good things there too.\" This was pure wishful thinking with no basis in reality—just lies their tongues spoke without any divine promise to support it.",
    "Without a doubt, for them is the Fire, where they will be abandoned.": "Allah declares with absolute certainty (la jarama) that their actual destination is the Hellfire. Instead of the rewards they imagined, they will be left in the Fire, neglected and forgotten. Their lies will not help them; their false hopes will turn to despair."
  },
  63: {
    "By Allah! We have surely sent messengers to communities before you ˹O Prophet˺,": "Allah swears that He sent messengers to nations before Muhammad (peace be upon him). No community was left without guidance. The history of humanity is filled with prophets calling people to truth.",
    "but Satan made their misdeeds appealing to them.": "Despite receiving messengers, many people rejected the truth because Satan beautified their sins in their eyes. Evil deeds appeared attractive; falsehood seemed reasonable; the wrong path looked appealing. This is Satan's primary strategy—to make bad things look good and good things look unappealing.",
    "So he is their patron today, and they will suffer a painful punishment.": "Those who followed Satan's deceptions made him their wali (patron, ally, guardian). In this world, they allied themselves with Satan against Allah. But this alliance brings no benefit—only painful punishment in the Hereafter. Satan will abandon them when they need help most."
  },
  64: {
    "We have revealed to you the Book only to clarify for them what they differed about,": "One of the main purposes of the Qur'an is to resolve disputes and clarify truth. People disagreed about God, religion, the afterlife, morality, and countless other matters. The Qur'an provides clear, authoritative answers to these disagreements, cutting through confusion and falsehood.",
    "and as a guide and mercy for those who believe.": "For believers, the Qur'an is both guidance (huda) showing them the right path, and mercy (rahma) bringing them Allah's compassion and favor. It guides them away from destruction and toward success in both worlds. This is why engagement with the Qur'an is essential for every Muslim."
  },
  65: {
    "And Allah sends down rain from the sky,": "Allah returns to the theme of His blessings, highlighting rain once again. Rain is repeatedly mentioned in the Qur'an because it is absolutely essential for life and because it is such a clear sign of Allah's power and mercy.",
    "giving life to the earth after its death.": "When land is barren, dry, and seemingly dead, rain transforms it. Plants sprout, flowers bloom, and life returns. This cycle happens every year in many regions, and it is a powerful reminder of resurrection. Just as Allah brings dead earth back to life, He will bring dead humans back to life on the Day of Judgment.",
    "Surely in this is a sign for those who listen.": "Those who truly listen (yasma'un)—meaning those who hear with understanding and reflection, not just physical hearing—will recognize this sign. Listening here implies accepting and acting on what one hears. The deaf in heart will see rain and think nothing of it; the believer will see it and remember Allah."
  },
  66: {
    "And there is certainly a lesson for you in cattle:": "Allah directs attention to cattle (cows, sheep, goats, camels) as a source of reflection and lessons. These animals are so common that we often overlook the miracles within them.",
    "We give you to drink of what is in their bellies, from between digested food and blood:": "The process of milk production is miraculous. Inside the animal, between partially digested food (farth) in the intestines and blood flowing through veins, pure milk is produced. These two substances—digested matter and blood—are not appetizing, yet from between them comes something completely different.",
    "pure milk, pleasant to drink.": "The milk that emerges is pure, clean, white, and delicious. It has no trace of the digested food or blood from which it was extracted. This purification process happens inside the animal without any human intervention. This is a sign of Allah's creative power—He produces the pure from the impure, the beautiful from the ordinary."
  },
  67: {
    "And from the fruits of palm trees and grapevines you derive intoxicants": "This verse was revealed before the complete prohibition of alcohol. It mentions that people make intoxicating drinks (sakar) from dates and grapes. This was a description of what they did, not an endorsement. Later, alcohol was prohibited in stages, and this verse is understood in that historical context.",
    "as well as wholesome provision.": "From the same fruits, people also derive halal, wholesome sustenance (rizq hasan)—fresh dates, raisins, grape juice, vinegar, and other beneficial products. The fruits themselves are blessings, and their lawful uses are many.",
    "Surely in this is a sign for those who understand.": "For people of intellect (ya'qilun), the same fruit producing both good and harmful products is a lesson. It teaches that Allah's blessings can be used rightly or wrongly. The choice is ours, and we will be held accountable for how we use what Allah provides."
  },
  68: {
    "And your Lord inspired the bees:": "Allah \"inspired\" (awha) the bees. This is a form of divine guidance given to creatures, not the revelation given to prophets, but an instinctive knowledge Allah placed within them. Bees have complex, sophisticated behaviors that they perform without being taught—a clear sign of divine programming.",
    "\"Make ˹your˺ homes in the mountains, the trees, and in what people construct,": "Allah directed bees to build their hives in mountains, hollow trees, and human-made structures. Bees build their honeycombs with precise hexagonal cells—the most efficient shape for storage—using geometry that engineers admire. They do this by Allah's inspiration, not by learning or thinking."
  },
  69: {
    "and feed from ˹the flower of˺ any fruit ˹you please˺": "Bees are told to eat from the nectar of various flowers and fruits. They travel from flower to flower, collecting nectar and pollen, pollinating plants in the process. This is essential for agriculture and ecosystems.",
    "and follow the ways your Lord has made easy for you.\"": "The paths of the bee—its ability to navigate, communicate directions to other bees through dance, and return home over long distances—are all made easy by Allah. Scientists marvel at the \"waggle dance\" bees use to communicate locations. All of this is Allah's inspiration at work.",
    "From their bellies comes forth liquid of varying colours,": "Honey comes from the bees' stomachs after a complex process of digestion and regurgitation. Honey varies in color—from light gold to dark amber—depending on the flowers the bees visited. Each type has its own flavor and properties.",
    "in which there is healing for people.": "The Qur'an declares that honey contains healing. This has been confirmed by modern science—honey has antibacterial, antifungal, anti-inflammatory, and wound-healing properties. It was used as medicine for centuries and continues to be valued today. The Prophet (peace be upon him) recommended honey for various ailments.",
    "Surely in this is a sign for those who reflect.": "For those who think deeply (yatafakkarun), the bee and its honey are amazing signs of Allah. A tiny insect, with a brain smaller than a pinhead, performs incredibly complex tasks and produces a substance that heals humans. This cannot be coincidence—it is divine design."
  },
  70: {
    "Allah has created you, and then causes you to die.": "Life and death are in Allah's hands alone. He brings us into existence, and He determines when we leave. No one can extend their life or hasten their death beyond what Allah has decreed. This is a reminder of our complete dependence on Allah.",
    "And some of you are left to reach the most feeble stage of life": "Some people live to extreme old age where they become frail, weak, and dependent. They lose their physical strength and mental sharpness. This is described as \"the most abject/feeble stage\" (ardhali al-'umur).",
    "so that they may know nothing after having known much.": "After a lifetime of learning, experiencing, and accumulating knowledge, some elderly people lose their memories and cognitive abilities. They forget things they once knew well—sometimes even forgetting their own children's names. This is a humbling reminder that our knowledge, our intelligence, our abilities—all are gifts from Allah that He can take back whenever He wills.",
    "Indeed, Allah is All-Knowing, Most Capable.": "While humans may lose their knowledge and capability with age, Allah's knowledge and power are eternal and unlimited. He knows everything and can do anything. This contrast highlights human weakness and divine perfection."
  },
  71: {
    "And Allah has favoured some of you over others in provision.": "Allah has distributed wealth and resources unequally among people. Some are rich, some are poor; some have abundant provision, others have little. This is by Allah's wisdom and is a test for both the wealthy (will they be grateful and generous?) and the poor (will they be patient and content?).",
    "But those who have been much favoured would not share their wealth with those ˹bondspeople˺ in their possession, making them their equals.": "Allah points out an inconsistency in human behavior. The wealthy would not share their wealth with their slaves or servants to make them equal. They maintain distinctions and refuse to treat those under them as equals. This is understandable on a human level—people do not easily give up advantages.",
    "Do they then deny Allah's favours?": "The rhetorical question exposes their logic: If humans will not make their servants equal to themselves, how can they attribute partners to Allah who are equal to Him? They understand inequality among themselves but then claim Allah has equals! This is denying Allah's unique favours and status. It is also a broader reminder that every blessing we have is from Allah, and denying His blessings—whether through shirk, ingratitude, or refusal to share with others—is a serious wrong."
  },
  72: {
    "And Allah has made for you spouses of your own kind,": "Allah created human beings in pairs—male and female—from the same species, so they can find companionship, comfort, and love with one another. Spouses are described elsewhere in the Qur'an as \"garments\" for each other (2:187), providing protection, warmth, and intimacy. This pairing is a divine blessing designed for human happiness and stability.",
    "and given you through your spouses children and grandchildren.": "Through marriage comes the blessing of offspring—children who bring joy, continue the family line, and care for parents in old age, and then grandchildren who multiply those blessings. The family structure is a gift from Allah that provides emotional support, social stability, and the continuation of humanity.",
    "And He has granted you good, lawful provisions.": "Beyond family, Allah has provided wholesome, pure (tayyibaat) sustenance—food, drink, and all the necessities of life that are lawful and good. Everything we need to survive and thrive has been made available by Allah's generosity.",
    "Are they then faithful to falsehood and ungrateful for Allah's favours?": "Despite all these obvious blessings, some people believe in falsehood—worshipping idols, following superstitions, and denying Allah's role. They enjoy Allah's gifts while crediting false gods or denying the Giver altogether. This is a profound ingratitude that defies logic and basic decency."
  },
  73: {
    "Yet they worship besides Allah those ˹idols˺ who do not afford them any provision from the heavens and the earth,": "The polytheists worship beings that cannot provide anything whatsoever. These false gods cannot send down rain from the sky, cannot cause crops to grow from the earth, cannot grant children, health, or any blessing. They are completely incapable of providing even the smallest provision.",
    "nor do they have the power to.": "Not only do these idols fail to provide, but they literally cannot. They have no power, no ability, no capacity to do anything. They are lifeless, powerless, and useless. Yet people devote themselves to these entities while ignoring the One who actually provides everything. This is the height of irrationality."
  },
  74: {
    "So do not set up equals to Allah,": "Allah commands people not to make comparisons that equate anything with Him. No idol, no human, no concept can be placed alongside Allah as an equal or partner. He is unique, incomparable, and beyond all comparisons that diminish His majesty.",
    "for Allah certainly knows and you do not know.": "Allah possesses complete knowledge while humans have limited understanding. When people make false analogies about Allah, they speak from ignorance. Allah knows the reality of all things—including the worthlessness of idols and the foolishness of shirk—while humans often do not grasp these truths. This is a call to humility and trust in divine guidance rather than human speculation."
  },
  75: {
    "Allah sets forth a parable: a slave who lacks all means,": "Allah presents a comparison to make the truth clear. Imagine a slave who is owned by another person, has no resources, no freedom, and no ability to do anything independently. He cannot give anything because he has nothing and owns nothing.",
    "compared to a ˹free˺ man to whom We granted a good provision, of which he donates ˹freely,˺ openly and secretly.": "Now compare that slave to a free man whom Allah has blessed with abundant wealth. This man can spend generously—publicly and privately—helping others and doing good. He has resources and the freedom to use them.",
    "Are they equal?": "Obviously, these two are not equal. Everyone would agree that the free, wealthy, generous man is superior to the powerless slave. This is the comparison between Allah and the idols. Allah is the One with all power, all provision, all ability to give and benefit. Idols are like the powerless slave—they have nothing and can do nothing.",
    "Praise be to Allah.": "This phrase (Al-hamdu lillah) affirms that all praise belongs to Allah alone, the One with true power and generosity, not to helpless idols.",
    "In fact, most of them do not know.": "Despite how obvious this comparison should be, most people still do not understand. They continue worshipping powerless idols instead of the All-Powerful Creator. Ignorance leads to shirk."
  },
  76: {
    "And Allah sets forth a parable of two men: one of them is dumb, incapable of anything.": "Allah presents another comparison. Imagine a man who cannot speak—he is mute. Beyond that, he is incapable of doing anything useful. He has no skills, no abilities, and cannot contribute in any way.",
    "He is a burden on his master.": "This person is a liability. Instead of helping his master, he requires constant care and attention. He takes but cannot give. He costs resources but produces nothing in return.",
    "Wherever he is sent, he brings no good.": "No matter what task he is assigned, no matter where he goes, he accomplishes nothing beneficial. Every mission fails. He is utterly useless.",
    "Can such a person be equal to the one who commands justice and is on the Straight Path?": "Compare this burdensome, useless person to someone who speaks wisdom, commands justice, guides people to what is right, and himself walks on the straight path of truth. Obviously, they are not equal. This is the comparison between idols (useless, burdensome, bringing no good) and Allah (who commands justice, guides to the straight path, and is the source of all good). How can anyone equate the two?"
  },
  77: {
    "To Allah ˹alone˺ belongs ˹the knowledge of˺ the unseen in the heavens and the earth.": "Only Allah knows the ghayb—the unseen realities, the future, the hidden secrets, and everything beyond human perception. No angel, no prophet, no jinn, and certainly no idol has access to this knowledge except what Allah reveals. The false gods people worship know nothing of the unseen.",
    "Bringing about the Hour would only take the blink of an eye, or even less.": "The Day of Judgment, despite being such a cosmic event, requires no effort from Allah. It can happen in an instant—faster than the blink of an eye. This emphasizes Allah's absolute power. Humans think such an event would require massive preparation and time, but for Allah, it is effortless.",
    "Surely Allah is Most Capable of everything.": "Allah's power (qudrah) extends over all things without exception. Nothing is difficult for Him. Creation, destruction, resurrection, judgment—all are equally easy for the Almighty. This should inspire both awe and trust in Allah's ability to fulfill all His promises."
  },
  78: {
    "And Allah brought you out of the wombs of your mothers while you knew nothing,": "Every human being entered this world completely ignorant. As newborns, we knew nothing—no language, no skills, no understanding of the world. We were utterly helpless and dependent. This is our common starting point, a reminder of our humble beginnings.",
    "and gave you hearing, sight, and intellect": "Allah then equipped us with the tools to learn and grow. Hearing (sam') allows us to receive knowledge through speech and sound. Sight (absar) allows us to observe and understand the world visually. Intellect/hearts (af'idah) allows us to process, reason, and understand what we hear and see. These three faculties are repeatedly mentioned together in the Qur'an as the means through which humans acquire knowledge and are held accountable.",
    "so perhaps you would be thankful.": "The purpose of these gifts is that we recognize the Giver and express gratitude. Every time we hear something beneficial, see something beautiful, or understand a concept, we should thank Allah. These faculties are not accidents of evolution—they are purposeful gifts from a generous Creator who deserves our thanks."
  },
  79: {
    "Have they not seen the birds glide in the open sky?": "Allah directs attention to a common sight that is actually miraculous—birds flying through the air. We see this so often that we take it for granted, but it is an extraordinary phenomenon worthy of reflection.",
    "None holds them up except Allah.": "What keeps birds suspended in the air? They defy gravity, soaring and gliding with apparent ease. While we can explain the physics of flight—air pressure, wing shape, lift—the ultimate cause is Allah. He designed birds with the perfect bodies for flight, created the air with properties that allow flight, and established the laws of physics that make it possible. Without Allah's will and design, birds would fall.",
    "Surely in this are signs for those who believe.": "For believers, bird flight is a sign (ayah) of Allah's creative power, wisdom, and control over creation. Every bird in the sky is evidence of divine design. Those with faith see Allah's hand in such everyday miracles and increase in their belief and gratitude."
  },
  80: {
    "And Allah has made your homes a place to rest,": "Permanent homes—houses and buildings—provide security, privacy, and rest. After a day of work and activity, we return to the comfort of our homes. This is a blessing from Allah. Having a safe place to live, sleep, and raise a family is not something everyone has, and those who have it should be grateful.",
    "and has given you tents from the hide of animals, light to handle when you travel and when you camp.": "For those who travel—nomads, traders, travelers—Allah provided portable shelters made from animal hides. These tents are light and easy to carry, set up, and take down. They provide protection during journeys and temporary stays. The Bedouin Arabs relied heavily on such tents, and this verse acknowledges that blessing.",
    "And out of their wool, fur, and hair He has given you furnishings and goods for a while.": "From sheep's wool, camel's fur, and goat's hair, people make carpets, blankets, clothing, ropes, and various household items. These materials provide comfort, warmth, and utility. The phrase \"for a while\" (ila heen) reminds us that all worldly possessions are temporary—we use them for this life, but they will not last forever."
  },
  81: {
    "And Allah has provided you shade out of what He created,": "Trees, buildings, clouds, mountains—all provide shade from the burning sun. In hot climates like Arabia, shade is a precious blessing. Without it, the heat would be unbearable. Allah created these sources of shade for human comfort.",
    "and has given you shelter in the mountains.": "Mountains contain caves and crevices that provide natural shelter from weather, enemies, and wild animals. Throughout history, people have used mountain caves for protection. Allah designed the earth with these features for human benefit.",
    "He has also provided you with clothes protecting you from the heat ˹and cold˺,": "Clothing protects us from extreme temperatures—both heat and cold. The verse mentions heat explicitly because in Arabia, protection from the scorching sun was paramount. But clothing serves the same purpose against cold. This is another blessing we often overlook.",
    "and armour shielding you in battle.": "Allah also provided the knowledge and materials to make armor and protective gear for warfare. Shields, helmets, chain mail—all protect soldiers in battle. Even the means of self-defense are blessings from Allah.",
    "This is how He perfects His favour upon you,": "All these blessings—shade, shelter, clothing, armor—are part of Allah's complete and perfect favor upon humanity. He has thought of everything we need and provided it.",
    "so perhaps you will ˹fully˺ submit ˹to Him˺.": "The purpose of recognizing these blessings is to lead us to Islam—full submission to Allah. When we see how much Allah has given us, the natural response should be gratitude expressed through worship and obedience. Recognizing Allah's favors should lead to surrendering to Him completely."
  },
  82: {
    "But if they turn away,": "If the disbelievers reject the message despite all the signs, proofs, and blessings that have been presented, it is their choice. They bear responsibility for their rejection.",
    "then your duty ˹O Prophet˺ is only to deliver ˹the message˺ clearly.": "The Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) is consoled that his job is only to convey the message clearly (al-balagh al-mubeen). He is not responsible for forcing people to believe or for their ultimate choices. He has done his duty by delivering Allah's words with clarity. The results are in Allah's hands. This principle applies to all who call to Islam—our job is to convey, not to convert."
  },
  83: {
    "They are aware of Allah's favours, but still deny them.": "This is a powerful indictment. The disbelievers actually recognize Allah's blessings—they know the food they eat, the water they drink, the families they have, and the safety they enjoy all come from a higher power. Deep down, they acknowledge these favors. Yet they deny them by worshipping others, by refusing to thank Allah, and by attributing these blessings to false causes.",
    "And most of them are ˹truly˺ ungrateful.": "The majority of them are kafiroon—a word that means both \"disbelievers\" and \"ungrateful ones.\" Kufr at its root is covering up or denying what one knows to be true. They cover up the truth of Allah's blessings and deny Him the gratitude He deserves. This ingratitude is the essence of their disbelief."
  },
  84: {
    "˹Consider, O Prophet,˺ the Day We will call ˹a prophet as˺ a witness from every faith-community.": "On the Day of Judgment, Allah will bring forward a witness from every nation—their prophet or messenger who was sent to them. This witness will testify about whether the message was delivered and how the people responded. No community will be able to claim they were not warned.",
    "Then the disbelievers will neither be allowed to plead": "The disbelievers will not be given permission to make excuses or argue their case. The time for arguments and justifications will have passed. In this world, they had every opportunity to reflect and repent; on that Day, the case is closed.",
    "nor appease ˹their Lord˺.": "They will not be able to do anything to please Allah or make amends. There will be no opportunity to return to the world and do better. The chance for repentance will have expired. This is why Islam emphasizes acting now, in this life, before it is too late."
  },
  85: {
    "And when the wrongdoers face the punishment,": "When the oppressors and disbelievers finally see the punishment they were warned about, when it becomes real before their eyes, they will be filled with terror and regret.",
    "it will not be lightened for them,": "There will be no reduction in their punishment. No appeals, no good behavior credits, no mercy at that point. The full punishment will be applied as decreed.",
    "nor will they be delayed ˹from it˺.": "They will not be given any extension or postponement. The punishment will come immediately and without pause. In this world, Allah delayed punishment to give them time to repent; on that Day, there are no more delays."
  },
  86: {
    "And when the polytheists see their associate-gods,": "On that Day, the polytheists will see the very idols and false gods they worshipped. These entities—whether they were idols, jinn, angels wrongly worshipped, or deceased saints—will be brought forth.",
    "they will say, \"Our Lord! These are our associate-gods that we used to invoke besides You.\"": "The polytheists will try to shift blame, pointing to their false gods and saying, \"These are the ones we worshipped! They led us astray!\" They attempt to make their idols share in the responsibility for their misguidance.",
    "Their gods will throw a rebuttal at them, ˹saying,˺ \"You are definitely liars.\"": "But the false gods will reject this accusation completely. They will call their former worshippers liars. The idols never asked to be worshipped; they never promised salvation; they never had any power. The polytheists invented these religions themselves. This dramatic confrontation exposes the futility of shirk."
  },
  87: {
    "They will offer ˹full˺ submission to Allah on that Day,": "On the Day of Judgment, everyone—including the most arrogant disbelievers—will submit to Allah. The pride and rebellion they showed in this world will vanish. They will surrender completely, but it will be too late for this submission to benefit them.",
    "and whatever ˹gods˺ they fabricated will fail them.": "All the lies they invented—the false gods, the fabricated religions, the made-up beliefs—will disappear and abandon them. These falsehoods will provide no help, no intercession, no benefit. Everything they relied upon besides Allah will prove worthless."
  },
  88: {
    "For those who disbelieve and hinder ˹others˺ from the Way of Allah,": "This verse addresses a particularly serious category: those who not only disbelieve themselves but actively prevent others from accepting Islam. They spread propaganda, persecute believers, and create obstacles to the truth. This is worse than personal disbelief.",
    "We will add more punishment to their punishment": "Their punishment will be multiplied—punishment upon punishment. They will suffer for their own disbelief plus additional torment for every person they led astray or prevented from guidance.",
    "for all the corruption they spread.": "The reason for this increased punishment is the corruption (fasad) they spread in the earth. They corrupted themselves and corrupted others. They damaged society and harmed the cause of truth. Every act of corruption adds to their account."
  },
  89: {
    "˹Consider, O Prophet,˺ the Day We will call against every faith-community a witness of their own.": "Each nation will have a witness from among themselves—their own prophet who lived with them, spoke their language, and delivered Allah's message to them. This witness will testify about what happened.",
    "And We will call you to be a witness against these ˹people of yours˺.": "Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) will be the witness for his ummah—the Muslim nation and all those who received his message. He will testify about how he delivered the message and how people responded. This is a tremendous responsibility and honor for the Prophet.",
    "We have revealed to you the Book as an explanation of all things,": "The Qur'an is described as \"tibyanan li kulli shay\" (an explanation of all things). It explains everything necessary for guidance—matters of faith, worship, morality, law, and the purpose of life. It provides clarity on all essential matters.",
    "a guide,": "The Qur'an is huda (guidance), showing the straight path to Allah, Paradise, and success in both worlds.",
    "a mercy,": "It is rahma (mercy) from Allah to humanity, offering them a way out of darkness, ignorance, and punishment.",
    "and good news for those who ˹fully˺ submit.": "For Muslims—those who submit to Allah—the Qur'an brings glad tidings of forgiveness, Paradise, and Allah's pleasure. It is a source of hope and encouragement for believers."
  },
  90: {
    "Indeed, Allah commands justice,": "Allah commands 'adl (justice)—giving everyone their due rights, being fair in dealings, judging equitably, and avoiding oppression. Justice is fundamental to Islam. It must be practiced with family, friends, strangers, and even enemies.",
    "grace,": "Beyond justice, Allah commands ihsan (excellence/grace). Ihsan means going beyond what is required—being generous when you could be merely fair, forgiving when you could demand your rights, excelling in worship as if you see Allah. Ihsan is the highest level of faith and conduct.",
    "as well as courtesy to close relatives.": "Allah specifically commands maintaining ties with relatives (silat al-rahm). Visiting family, helping them financially and emotionally, and keeping good relations with kin is a religious obligation. Cutting family ties is a serious sin.",
    "He forbids indecency,": "Allah prohibits fahsha (indecency)—shameful acts, particularly sexual sins like adultery, fornication, and anything that leads to them. These acts corrupt individuals and society.",
    "wickedness,": "Munkar refers to anything evil, wrong, or disapproved by Islamic law. This includes all sins and bad conduct that go against Allah's commands.",
    "and aggression.": "Baghy means transgression, oppression, and wrongful aggression against others. Taking what is not yours, harming others unjustly, and exceeding proper limits are all forbidden.",
    "He instructs you so perhaps you will be mindful.": "Allah gives these instructions as reminders (wa'z) so that people will remember and take heed. This verse is considered one of the most comprehensive in the Qur'an, summarizing the foundations of Islamic ethics. It was so beloved that Caliph Umar ibn Abd al-Aziz ordered it to be recited at the end of every Friday sermon, a practice that continues today."
  },
  91: {
    "Honour Allah's covenant when you make a pledge,": "When you enter into any agreement, treaty, or pledge—whether it is a promise to Allah, a contract with another person, or an oath of allegiance—you must fulfill it. Allah commands that covenants be honored completely. Breaking promises is a sign of hypocrisy. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"The signs of a hypocrite are three: when he speaks, he lies; when he makes a promise, he breaks it; and when he is entrusted, he betrays.\" (Bukhari & Muslim)",
    "and do not break your oaths after confirming them,": "Once you have firmly established an oath or pledge, you must not go back on it. An oath that is confirmed and witnessed carries great weight. Breaking it is a serious sin that damages trust in society and angers Allah.",
    "having made Allah your guarantor.": "When you swear by Allah or make Him a witness to your agreement, you have elevated that covenant to the highest level. Allah Himself becomes the guarantor of your word. To then break that oath is to disrespect Allah directly and make light of His name.",
    "Surely Allah knows all you do.": "Nothing is hidden from Allah. Even if people do not see you break your word, even if you manage to deceive others, Allah sees everything. He knows every secret intention and every hidden action. This knowledge should motivate us to be truthful and honorable in all our dealings."
  },
  92: {
    "Do not be like the woman who ˹foolishly˺ unravels her yarn after it is firmly spun,": "Allah presents a vivid parable. Imagine a woman who works hard to spin yarn into strong thread, then foolishly unravels everything she made. All her effort is wasted; she has nothing to show for her labor. This refers to a woman in Makkah known for this strange behavior. The image represents the foolishness of building something valuable (like trust and agreements) and then destroying it.",
    "by taking your oaths as a means of deceiving one another": "Some people use oaths strategically—making promises when it benefits them, then breaking those promises when circumstances change. They swear allegiance to one group, then switch to another when the second group becomes more powerful. This is using oaths as tools of deception rather than sacred commitments.",
    "in favour of a stronger group.": "The specific context is when people abandon their commitments because a more powerful or beneficial alliance becomes available. This opportunistic behavior destroys social trust. A person's word should not depend on which side is winning.",
    "Surely Allah tests you through this.": "These situations are tests from Allah. Will you remain faithful to your word even when it is difficult or disadvantageous? Will you honor your commitments even when breaking them might bring worldly gain? This is how Allah distinguishes the sincere from the hypocritical.",
    "And on the Day of Judgment He will certainly make your differences clear to you.": "Whatever disputes, broken promises, and disagreements exist in this world will be fully exposed and judged on the Day of Resurrection. The truth will be made absolutely clear, and everyone will receive what they deserve based on how they honored or violated their covenants."
  },
  93: {
    "Had Allah willed, He could have easily made you one community ˹of believers˺,": "If Allah wanted, He could have created all humans as believers with no capacity to disbelieve. He could have made everyone identical in faith, like the angels who have no choice but to obey. But that was not His plan.",
    "but He leaves to stray whoever He wills and guides whoever He wills.": "Instead, Allah gave humans free will. Those who sincerely seek guidance are guided by Allah. Those who choose to reject truth and follow their desires are left in their misguidance. This \"leaving to stray\" is a consequence of their own choices—Allah does not force anyone into disbelief, but He allows people to follow the path they choose. Guidance is a blessing given to those who want it; misguidance is a consequence for those who reject it.",
    "And you will certainly be questioned about what you used to do.": "Because humans have free will, they are accountable. On the Day of Judgment, every person will be asked about their actions. This questioning confirms that we are responsible for our choices. If we had no free will, there would be no point in accountability. But we do have choice, so we must answer for how we used it."
  },
  94: {
    "And do not take your oaths as a means of deceiving one another": "Allah repeats and emphasizes this prohibition. Using oaths—swearing by Allah's name—to deceive others is a grave sin. It mocks the sacred and destroys social trust. When people cannot rely on each other's words, society crumbles.",
    "or your feet will slip after they have been firm.": "This is a powerful metaphor. When you break oaths and deceive others, your own position becomes unstable. You may think you are gaining advantage, but you are actually losing your footing. A person who was once secure in their faith, their reputation, and their standing can fall into ruin because of broken promises.",
    "Then you will taste the evil ˹consequences˺ of hindering ˹others˺ from the Way of Allah,": "When believers break their word, it harms the image of Islam. Others see Muslims being dishonest and are turned away from the faith. This hindrance from Allah's path brings severe consequences on those responsible. Every person who was discouraged from Islam because of a Muslim's bad behavior becomes a burden on that Muslim's account.",
    "and you will suffer a tremendous punishment.": "Beyond worldly consequences, there is a tremendous punishment in the Hereafter for those who abuse oaths and deceive others. This punishment reflects the severity of the sin."
  },
  95: {
    "And do not trade Allah's covenant for a fleeting gain.": "Some people break their promises or abandon their faith for worldly benefits—money, power, status, or safety. They sell their integrity and their covenant with Allah for something temporary. This is described as \"a fleeting gain\" (thaman qaleel) because no worldly benefit, no matter how large it seems, compares to what Allah offers.",
    "What is with Allah is certainly far better for you, if only you knew.": "The rewards Allah has prepared for the faithful—Paradise, His pleasure, eternal happiness—are incomparably better than anything this world offers. If people truly understood this, they would never compromise their principles for worldly gain. The problem is lack of true knowledge and conviction."
  },
  96: {
    "Whatever you have will end,": "Everything in this world is temporary. Wealth will be spent or inherited by others. Health will decline. Youth will fade. Power will pass to someone else. Possessions will break, decay, or be lost. Nothing we have lasts forever.",
    "but whatever Allah has is everlasting.": "In contrast, what Allah possesses is eternal. The rewards of Paradise never end. The pleasure of Allah lasts forever. The blessings of the Hereafter are permanent. This contrast should guide our priorities—why chase what is temporary while neglecting what is eternal?",
    "And We will certainly reward the steadfast according to the best of their deeds.": "Those who are patient (sabirun)—who endure hardships, resist temptations, and remain faithful to Allah's covenant—will be rewarded based on the best of their deeds. Allah's generosity means He highlights our best actions and rewards us based on them, overlooking lesser deeds. This is encouragement to persevere."
  },
  97: {
    "Whoever does good, whether male or female, and is a believer,": "This verse establishes complete equality between men and women in terms of reward for good deeds. Both genders have equal access to Allah's mercy and reward. The condition is twofold: doing good deeds (amal salih) and having faith (iman). Good deeds without faith are not accepted, and claimed faith without good deeds is incomplete.",
    "We will surely bless them with a good life,": "Allah promises a \"hayat tayyibah\" (a good, pure, wholesome life) to the believing person who does good. This good life is not necessarily about wealth or worldly success—it means contentment, peace of heart, satisfaction, and blessing in whatever one has. A poor believer with contentment has a better life than a rich disbeliever filled with anxiety. The Prophet (peace be upon him) said: \"Whoever wakes up secure in his dwelling, healthy in his body, having his day's provision, it is as if he has been given the entire world.\"",
    "and We will certainly reward them according to the best of their deeds.": "In the Hereafter, their reward will be calculated based on their best actions. Allah's justice is mixed with generosity—He looks at our best, forgives our shortcomings, and rewards abundantly. This should motivate us to keep striving for excellence in our deeds."
  },
  98: {
    "When you recite the Quran, seek refuge with Allah from Satan, the accursed.": "Before beginning to recite the Qur'an, Muslims are instructed to say: \"A'udhu billahi min ash-Shaytan ir-rajeem\" (I seek refuge in Allah from Satan, the accursed). This is because Satan tries to distract us during recitation, cause us to misunderstand the meaning, prevent us from benefiting from the words, or make us recite incorrectly. By seeking Allah's protection, we shield ourselves from these satanic influences. The Qur'an is a source of guidance and healing, and Satan desperately wants to prevent us from receiving its benefits."
  },
  99: {
    "He certainly has no authority over those who believe and put their trust in their Lord.": "Satan's power is limited. He cannot force anyone to sin. He can only whisper, suggest, and tempt. For those who have genuine faith (iman) and place their trust (tawakkul) in Allah, Satan has no real authority. They may be tempted, but they are not controlled. Their faith and reliance on Allah protect them. This is reassuring—Satan is not all-powerful. With faith and trust in Allah, believers can resist his influence."
  },
  100: {
    "His authority is only over those who take him as a patron": "Satan has power only over those who willingly follow him, who make him their ally and protector instead of Allah. When people choose to obey Satan's suggestions, they give him authority over themselves. It is a choice they make.",
    "and who—under his influence—associate ˹others˺ with Allah ˹in worship˺.": "Those who commit shirk—associating partners with Allah—are under Satan's influence. He leads them to worship false gods, follow false religions, and abandon the worship of Allah alone. Shirk is Satan's greatest achievement, and those who fall into it have made Satan their master. This verse clarifies that Satan's influence is not forced upon anyone—people choose to follow him by abandoning Allah."
  },
  101: {
    "When We replace a verse with another—": "This refers to the concept of abrogation (naskh), where Allah reveals a new ruling that supersedes a previous one. This happened in stages during the Prophet's life as circumstances changed and the Muslim community developed. For example, the direction of prayer was changed from Jerusalem to Makkah, and the prohibition of alcohol was revealed gradually.",
    "and Allah knows best what He reveals—": "Allah has perfect wisdom in what He reveals and when. He knows the needs of humanity at every stage. The changes in rulings are not random or contradictory—they reflect Allah's wisdom in guiding people progressively.",
    "they say, \"You ˹Muḥammad˺ are just a fabricator.\"": "The disbelievers used abrogation as an excuse to accuse the Prophet of making up the Qur'an. They said, \"If this were really from God, why would it change? You must be inventing it yourself.\" This was a misunderstanding of divine wisdom and a malicious accusation.",
    "In fact, most of them do not know.": "Their accusation stems from ignorance. They do not understand how divine guidance works, how laws can be adjusted for different circumstances, or how Allah's wisdom operates. Most people who reject truth do so out of ignorance rather than genuine understanding."
  },
  102: {
    "Say, \"The holy spirit has brought it down from your Lord with the truth": "The Prophet is instructed to respond to their accusations. The \"holy spirit\" (Ruh al-Qudus) refers to the angel Jibreel (Gabriel), who brought the Qur'an from Allah. This revelation is not human invention—it comes directly from the Lord of all creation, and it is brought with truth, not falsehood.",
    "to reassure the believers,": "One purpose of revelation—including abrogation—is to strengthen the hearts of believers. When they see how Allah guides them through different stages, their faith increases. Each revelation confirmed that Allah was with them, caring for them, and guiding them through every situation.",
    "and as a guide and good news for those who submit ˹to Allah˺.\"": "For Muslims, the Qur'an serves as guidance (huda) for all matters of life and as good news (bushra) of Allah's mercy, forgiveness, and Paradise. It is a source of direction and hope for those who submit to Allah."
  },
  103: {
    "And We surely know that they say, \"No one is teaching him except a human.\"": "Allah is aware of their accusations. The disbelievers claimed that Muhammad (peace be upon him) was learning the Qur'an from some human teacher—perhaps a Christian slave or a foreign tradesman. They tried to attribute the Qur'an to human authorship.",
    "But the man they refer to speaks a foreign tongue,": "Allah exposes the absurdity of their claim. The person they point to as the supposed teacher spoke a foreign language—he was not a native Arabic speaker. His language skills were limited, and he could not compose eloquent Arabic.",
    "whereas this ˹Quran˺ is ˹in˺ eloquent Arabic.": "The Qur'an is in the most eloquent, sophisticated, and beautiful Arabic ever produced. It surpasses all human poetry and prose. How could a foreigner with broken Arabic teach Muhammad to produce this linguistic masterpiece? The claim is logically impossible. The Qur'an's language is itself a miracle that proves its divine origin."
  },
  104: {
    "Surely those who do not believe in Allah's revelations will never be guided by Allah,": "Those who stubbornly reject Allah's signs and revelations despite clear evidence will not receive guidance. Guidance is a gift Allah gives to those who seek it sincerely. Those who reject truth and close their hearts are left in their misguidance as a consequence of their choice.",
    "and they will suffer a painful punishment.": "Beyond being deprived of guidance, they will face painful punishment in the Hereafter. Rejection of divine revelation has severe consequences—both missing out on the blessings of guidance and facing the torment of Hell."
  },
  105: {
    "No one fabricates lies except those who disbelieve in Allah's revelations,": "Allah turns the accusation back on the accusers. The disbelievers called the Prophet a fabricator, but in reality, those who fabricate lies about Allah and His religion are the disbelievers themselves. They invent false gods, make up false religions, and attribute lies to Allah. The Prophet, who believes in Allah's revelations, would never fabricate lies about them.",
    "and it is they who are the ˹true˺ liars.": "The real liars are not the prophets but those who deny them. The disbelievers lied about Allah, lied about the Prophet, and lied about the Qur'an. Their accusations of fabrication are themselves fabrications. This verse completely reverses their charge and exposes their hypocrisy."
  },
  106: {
    "Whoever disbelieves in Allah after their belief—": "This verse addresses the serious matter of apostasy—leaving Islam after having believed. A person who knew the truth, accepted it, and then chose to abandon it is in a grave state. This is not about someone who never believed, but about someone who believed and then turned away.",
    "not those who are forced while their hearts are firm in faith,": "There is a critical exception. If a person is compelled under threat of death, torture, or severe harm to outwardly renounce Islam, but their heart remains firm in faith, they are not guilty of disbelief. This verse was revealed regarding Ammar ibn Yasir (may Allah be pleased with him), who was tortured by the Quraysh until he spoke words of disbelief to save his life. He came to the Prophet (peace be upon him) crying, and the Prophet asked, \"How do you find your heart?\" Ammar replied, \"Firm in faith.\" The Prophet said, \"If they do it again, say it again.\" This establishes the principle that outward words spoken under duress do not constitute disbelief if the heart remains believing.",
    "but those who embrace disbelief wholeheartedly—": "The condemnation is for those who willingly, happily, and fully open their hearts to disbelief. They are not forced; they choose to leave Islam because they prefer something else—worldly gain, social acceptance, or their own desires. Their chests are \"expanded\" with disbelief, meaning they embrace it completely.",
    "they will be condemned by Allah and suffer a tremendous punishment.": "Upon such people is Allah's wrath (ghadab), and for them is a tremendous punishment in the Hereafter. This shows the severity of willful apostasy—abandoning truth after knowing it is among the worst sins."
  },
  107: {
    "This is because they prefer the life of this world over the Hereafter.": "Allah explains the root cause of their apostasy: they loved this world more than the next. They chose temporary pleasures, comforts, or safety over eternal salvation. They prioritized what they could see and touch over what Allah promised. This misplaced priority led them to abandon their faith.",
    "Surely Allah never guides those who ˹choose to˺ disbelieve.": "When people deliberately choose disbelief over faith, Allah does not force guidance upon them. Guidance is offered to those who seek it; those who reject it are left in their misguidance. This is divine justice—people get what they choose."
  },
  108: {
    "They are the ones whose hearts, ears, and eyes are sealed by Allah,": "As a consequence of their choices, Allah seals their hearts so they cannot understand truth, their ears so they cannot benefit from hearing it, and their eyes so they cannot see the signs around them. This sealing is not arbitrary—it is a result of their persistent rejection. They closed these faculties to guidance first, and Allah confirmed their state.",
    "and it is they who are ˹truly˺ heedless.": "They are ghafilun (heedless, negligent, unaware). Despite all the warnings, signs, and opportunities, they remained oblivious to what matters most—their relationship with Allah and their eternal destiny. Heedlessness is a dangerous spiritual disease that leads to destruction."
  },
  109: {
    "Without a doubt, they will be the losers in the Hereafter.": "There is no question about their fate. Whatever they gained in this world by abandoning their faith will be worthless. They are the ultimate losers (khasirun). They traded eternal Paradise for temporary worldly benefits—the worst possible trade. On the Day of Judgment, their loss will be absolute and irreversible."
  },
  110: {
    "As for those who emigrated after being compelled ˹to renounce Islam˺,": "This verse offers hope and comfort to those who were forced to say words of disbelief under persecution but then escaped and emigrated for Allah's sake. Like Ammar and others who were tortured, they were victims of circumstance, not willing apostates.",
    "then struggled ˹in Allah's cause˺, and persevered,": "After their trial, they proved their faith by making hijrah (emigration), striving in Allah's cause (jihad), and remaining patient through all difficulties. Their subsequent actions demonstrated the sincerity of their hearts.",
    "your Lord ˹O Prophet˺ is truly All-Forgiving, Most Merciful after all.": "For such people, Allah is Ghafur (All-Forgiving) and Raheem (Most Merciful). Whatever they said under duress is forgiven. Their perseverance is rewarded. This shows the balance in Islam—severity for willful apostasy, but mercy and understanding for those who were compelled and then returned to full practice of their faith."
  },
  111: {
    "˹Consider˺ the Day ˹when˺ every soul will come pleading for itself,": "On the Day of Judgment, every person will be completely focused on their own case. There will be no time to worry about others. Each soul will come arguing, defending, and pleading on its own behalf. The bonds of family and friendship will be forgotten as everyone is consumed with concern for themselves. Allah says elsewhere: \"On that Day, a person will flee from his brother, his mother and father, his wife and children. Each one of them will have enough concern of their own.\" (80:34-37)",
    "and each will be paid in full for what it did,": "Every soul will receive complete recompense for its deeds—good for good, and bad for bad. Nothing will be overlooked or forgotten. The record is complete and accurate.",
    "and none will be wronged.": "Allah's justice is perfect. No one will be treated unfairly. No good deed will go unrewarded, and no one will be punished for something they did not do. This is the ultimate reassurance of divine justice—even if we experience injustice in this world, perfect justice awaits on that Day."
  },
  112: {
    "And Allah sets forth the example of a society which was safe and at ease,": "Allah presents a parable of a town (many scholars say this refers to Makkah) that enjoyed complete security. Its people lived without fear of invasion, crime, or instability. They were at ease, comfortable, and prosperous.",
    "receiving its provision in abundance from all directions.": "Provisions came to this town from everywhere—trade caravans, travelers, and various sources. They never lacked food, water, or goods. Their economy thrived, and their needs were met from multiple directions.",
    "But its people met Allah's favours with ingratitude,": "Despite all these blessings, the people of this town were ungrateful. They did not thank Allah, did not worship Him properly, and did not acknowledge that all their blessings came from Him. They attributed their success to their own efforts or to false gods.",
    "so Allah made them taste the clutches of hunger and fear for their misdeeds.": "Allah transformed their situation completely. Instead of abundance, they experienced hunger. Instead of security, they lived in fear. These punishments \"clothed\" them like garments—surrounding them completely. This was a direct consequence of their ingratitude and sins. For Makkah, this may refer to the years of famine the Quraysh experienced, or it could be a general warning applicable to any ungrateful society."
  },
  113: {
    "A messenger of their own actually did come to them,": "Allah sent them a messenger from among themselves—someone who spoke their language, understood their culture, and was known to them. This made the message accessible and relatable. For the Makkans, this was Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him).",
    "but they denied him.": "Despite the messenger being one of their own, they rejected him. They called him a liar, a poet, a madman—anything to avoid accepting his message. This denial was stubborn and persistent.",
    "So the torment overtook them while they persisted in wrongdoing.": "Punishment came upon them while they were still engaged in their oppression and sins. They did not repent; they did not change. The torment found them in their state of wrongdoing. This is a warning to all societies—blessings can be removed and replaced with punishment when ingratitude and denial persist."
  },
  114: {
    "So eat from the good, lawful things which Allah has provided for you,": "Allah commands believers to eat from what is halal (lawful) and tayyib (good, pure, wholesome). Islam does not require asceticism or deprivation—rather, it encourages enjoying Allah's blessings within the boundaries He set. The world is full of good things that Allah has made permissible for us.",
    "and be grateful for Allah's favours,": "Along with enjoying these blessings, we must express gratitude. Saying \"Bismillah\" before eating and \"Alhamdulillah\" after eating are simple but important expressions of thanks. Gratitude protects us from the fate of the ungrateful town mentioned earlier.",
    "if you ˹truly˺ worship Him ˹alone˺.": "True worship of Allah includes obeying His commands about what to eat and being thankful for His provisions. Worship is not limited to prayer and fasting—it encompasses how we eat, earn, and live. If we claim to worship Allah, we should follow His guidance in all matters."
  },
  115: {
    "He has only forbidden you ˹to eat˺ carrion,": "Animals that die naturally without proper slaughter (maytah) are prohibited. This includes animals that died from disease, old age, or accidents. Proper Islamic slaughter involves invoking Allah's name and draining the blood, which removes harmful substances.",
    "blood,": "Flowing blood is prohibited for consumption. This is why Islamic slaughter emphasizes draining the blood from the animal. Blood that remains in the meat after proper slaughter is overlooked, but drinking or eating blood itself is forbidden.",
    "swine,": "Pork and all pig products are absolutely forbidden in Islam. The pig is considered impure, and this prohibition is clear and unconditional. Modern science has identified various health concerns with pork, but the primary reason is simply Allah's command.",
    "and what is slaughtered in the name of any other than Allah.": "Any animal slaughtered while invoking a name other than Allah's—such as idols, saints, or other beings—is forbidden. The act of slaughter is an act of worship, and dedicating it to other than Allah is a form of shirk.",
    "But if someone is compelled by necessity—neither driven by desire nor exceeding immediate need—": "Islam provides an exception for genuine emergencies. If someone is starving and has no lawful food available, they may eat from the forbidden items to survive. However, this permission has conditions: they must not desire the forbidden food, and they must eat only what is necessary to survive, not more.",
    "then surely Allah is All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "Even in such emergency situations, Allah is forgiving and merciful. He does not burden people beyond their capacity. This shows the balance in Islamic law—clear prohibitions, but reasonable exceptions for genuine necessity."
  },
  116: {
    "Do not falsely declare with your tongues, \"This is lawful, and that is unlawful,\"": "Allah warns against making religious rulings based on personal opinion or cultural tradition without divine authority. The Arab polytheists used to declare certain animals or practices lawful or unlawful based on their own whims and inventions. This is a serious transgression.",
    "˹only˺ fabricating lies against Allah.": "When someone claims something is halal or haram without evidence from Allah, they are attributing lies to Him. They are putting words in Allah's mouth. This is extremely dangerous—it involves both lying and claiming to speak for God.",
    "Indeed, those who fabricate lies against Allah will never succeed.": "Such people will never achieve true success (falah)—neither in this world nor the Hereafter. Their fabrications may give them temporary influence or benefit, but ultimate success requires truth and submission to Allah's actual commands."
  },
  117: {
    "˹It is only˺ a brief enjoyment,": "Whatever worldly benefit they gain from their fabrications—power, followers, money, or status—is temporary and insignificant in the grand scheme. It is \"mata' qaleel\" (a small, brief enjoyment) that will soon end.",
    "then they will suffer a painful punishment.": "After their brief enjoyment, they will face severe punishment for their lies against Allah. The contrast is stark: a little pleasure now, followed by lasting pain. This is the worst possible trade."
  },
  118: {
    "To the Jews, We have forbidden what We related to you before.": "Allah refers to the dietary restrictions placed on the Jews, which were mentioned in Surah Al-An'am (6:146)—such as the prohibition of animals with undivided hooves, and the fat of cattle and sheep except what is on their backs. These were additional restrictions not placed on Muslims.",
    "We did not wrong them,": "Allah clarifies that these extra prohibitions were not arbitrary or oppressive. Allah does not wrong anyone. Every divine ruling has wisdom behind it.",
    "but it was they who wronged themselves.": "These restrictions were imposed as a consequence of the Jews' own disobedience and sins. Their wrongdoing led to a heavier burden. This is a lesson that persistent sin can lead to loss of blessings and additional restrictions. Muslims should be grateful for the relatively few dietary prohibitions in Islam and avoid the path that leads to losing Allah's concessions."
  },
  119: {
    "As for those who commit evil ignorantly ˹or recklessly˺,": "This refers to people who sin out of ignorance, foolishness, or the impulsiveness of desire—not out of deliberate defiance of Allah. Most sins are committed in moments of weakness or lack of awareness, not as conscious rebellion against God.",
    "then repent afterwards": "After committing the sin, they feel remorse, turn to Allah, and sincerely repent (tawbah). They regret what they did and ask Allah for forgiveness.",
    "and mend their ways,": "True repentance includes reformation (islah)—not just saying sorry, but actually changing behavior and making amends where possible. Words of repentance must be followed by actions of improvement.",
    "then your Lord is surely All-Forgiving, Most Merciful.": "For such people, Allah is Ghafur (All-Forgiving) and Raheem (Most Merciful). No matter how serious the sin, sincere repentance opens the door to Allah's forgiveness. This is one of the most hopeful messages in the Qur'an—no one should despair of Allah's mercy."
  },
  120: {
    "Indeed, Abraham was a model of excellence:": "Ibrahim (peace be upon him) is described as an \"ummah\"—a word that usually means \"nation\" or \"community.\" Here it means he was an entire community unto himself; he embodied all virtues that an entire nation might possess. He was a leader, a role model, and a source of guidance all in one person.",
    "devoted to Allah,": "He was \"qanit\"—constantly obedient, devout, and humble before Allah. His life was characterized by continuous worship and submission.",
    "˹perfectly˺ upright—": "He was \"hanif\"—inclined away from all falsehood and firmly established upon monotheism and truth. He turned away from the paganism of his society and held fast to pure worship of Allah alone.",
    "not a polytheist—": "Allah explicitly states that Ibrahim was not among the mushrikeen (polytheists). This is significant because various groups—Jews, Christians, and Arab polytheists—all claimed Ibrahim as their own. Allah clarifies that Ibrahim belonged to none of these deviant paths; he was a pure monotheist."
  },
  121: {
    "˹utterly˺ grateful for Allah's favours.": "Ibrahim was characterized by gratitude (shukr). He recognized Allah's blessings and constantly thanked Him for them. This is particularly relevant in Surah An-Nahl, which catalogs so many of Allah's favors—Ibrahim exemplified the proper response to those favors.",
    "˹So˺ He chose him": "Because of Ibrahim's qualities—his devotion, uprightness, and gratitude—Allah chose him (ijtabahu) for prophethood and special status. He became the father of prophets and the leader of monotheists.",
    "and guided him to the Straight Path.": "Allah guided Ibrahim to the sirat al-mustaqeem—the straight path of truth and salvation. This guidance was both a reward for his sincerity and a blessing that benefited all of humanity through his legacy."
  },
  122: {
    "We blessed him with all goodness in this world,": "Ibrahim was given \"hasanah\" (goodness) in this world—a righteous family, honored descendants, a legacy of prophethood, respect and remembrance among all religious communities, and all believers sending salutations upon him in their prayers until the Day of Judgment.",
    "and in the Hereafter he will certainly be among the righteous.": "Beyond worldly blessings, Ibrahim is guaranteed a place among the saliheen (righteous) in the Hereafter. He will have the highest stations in Paradise. This shows that true servants of Allah receive good in both worlds."
  },
  123: {
    "Then We revealed to you ˹O Prophet, saying˺: \"Follow the faith of Abraham, the upright,": "Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) was commanded to follow the millah (religious way) of Ibrahim. Islam is not a new religion—it is the restoration and completion of the original monotheism that Ibrahim championed. The Prophet continued Ibrahim's legacy of pure worship of Allah alone.",
    "who was not one of the polytheists.\"": "Again, Allah emphasizes that Ibrahim had nothing to do with shirk. Any group that practices polytheism or attributes partners to Allah cannot legitimately claim Ibrahim as their forefather in faith."
  },
  124: {
    "˹Honouring˺ the Sabbath was ordained only for those who disputed about Abraham.": "The Sabbath (Saturday) observance was given specifically to the Jews, who disputed about Ibrahim and deviated from his way. It was not part of Ibrahim's original practice. The Sabbath became a test and a burden for them due to their disputes and disobedience. Muslims follow Friday as their day of congregation, not because of disputes, but as Allah's choice for this ummah.",
    "And surely your Lord will judge between them on the Day of Judgment regarding their disputes.": "All the disputes among various religious groups about Ibrahim, about the Sabbath, and about true religion will be settled definitively by Allah on the Day of Judgment. Until then, each group claims to be right, but Allah will make the truth clear."
  },
  125: {
    "Invite ˹all˺ to the Way of your Lord with wisdom": "The first method of da'wah (calling to Islam) is hikmah (wisdom). This means understanding your audience, choosing the right time and place, using appropriate language, and presenting the message in a way that resonates with the listener's intellect. Wisdom means knowing what to say, how to say it, and when to say it.",
    "and kind advice,": "The second method is maw'idhah hasanah (good, kind advice). This involves touching people's hearts with reminders that move them emotionally—stories, examples, warnings, and encouragements delivered with gentleness and compassion. It is preaching that softens hearts rather than hardens them.",
    "and only debate with them in the best manner.": "When dialogue or argument is necessary, it must be conducted in the best way (billati hiya ahsan). This means avoiding harshness, insults, or aggression. The goal is to convince, not to defeat or humiliate. Even in disagreement, a Muslim maintains good character and respect.",
    "Surely your Lord ˹alone˺ knows best who has strayed from His Way": "Ultimately, guidance is from Allah. The da'ee (caller) does their best, but Allah knows who is truly astray and who is receptive to guidance. Our job is to convey the message properly; results are in Allah's hands.",
    "and who is ˹rightly˺ guided.": "Allah also knows who is guided. We cannot judge people's hearts or predict who will accept the truth. Sometimes the most unlikely people become believers, while those we expected to believe remain in denial. This knowledge belongs to Allah alone."
  },
  126: {
    "If you retaliate, then let it be equivalent to what you have suffered.": "Islam permits retaliation for wrongs suffered, but with strict limits. If someone harms you, you may respond in kind—no more, no less. Excessive retaliation is prohibited. This ensures justice without escalation. If someone insults you once, you may respond with one insult, not ten. If someone strikes you, you may strike back equally, not more severely.",
    "But if you patiently endure, it is certainly best for those who are patient.": "While retaliation is permitted, patience (sabr) is better. Forgiving those who wrong you, restraining your anger, and trusting Allah to handle justice—these are superior responses. This verse was revealed when the Prophet (peace be upon him) saw the mutilated body of his uncle Hamza at Uhud and wanted to retaliate severely. He was guided to restraint. Patience brings greater reward from Allah and prevents cycles of revenge."
  },
  127: {
    "Be patient ˹O Prophet˺,": "Allah commands the Prophet (peace be upon him) to be patient. This command extends to all believers. Patience is essential for navigating the difficulties of life and the challenges of calling people to truth.",
    "for your patience is only with Allah's help.": "True patience is not mere human willpower—it comes from Allah. We cannot be truly patient without His assistance. This is why we ask Allah for patience and rely on Him to grant us the strength to endure.",
    "Do not grieve over those ˹who disbelieve˺,": "The Prophet cared deeply about his people and grieved when they rejected the message. Allah consoles him: do not let their rejection cause you excessive sadness. You have done your duty; their choices are their own.",
    "nor be distressed by their schemes.": "The disbelievers plotted against the Prophet and the believers. Allah tells him not to be anxious or constricted by their plots. Allah is aware of everything they plan, and He is the best of planners. Their schemes cannot succeed against Allah's protection."
  },
  128: {
    "Surely Allah is with those who shun evil": "The surah concludes with a beautiful promise. Allah is with the muttaqeen—those who have taqwa, who are mindful of Allah and avoid what He has prohibited. His \"being with\" them means His support, protection, guidance, and care.",
    "and who do good ˹deeds˺.": "Allah is also with the muhsineen—those who do ihsan, who excel in their worship and their character. Ihsan means doing things beautifully and with excellence, worshipping Allah as if you see Him, and treating others with the best conduct. Those who combine taqwa (avoiding evil) with ihsan (doing good excellently) have the companionship and support of Allah. This is the ultimate success and the perfect conclusion to Surah An-Nahl—the Surah of Blessings."
  }
};